<DOCNO> AP900627-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in a major effort to crack down on art thefts 
france has published the first catalog of art works stolen from its 
national collections 
the authors of the catalog found that most recent thefts were 
from museum storage rooms not exhibit halls and were probably 
inside jobs it lists 200 works stolen between 1979 and 1989 from 
museums throughout the country 
five hundred copies of the catalog are being distributed to 
police museum and customs officials art dealers auctioneers and 
experts in a new effort to track down stolen art and crack down on 
resale on the international market according to andre treps of the 
interior ministry 
written by museum curators jacqueline munck and vincent pomarede 
and published tuesday the catalog urges art professionals to take 
a more forthright approach to the problem 
too often people in charge of the art collections after a 
theft feel guilty and have an understandable desire to cover it 
up the curators wrote 
many french museums do not like to discuss art thefts and blame 
the media for falsely drawing attention to security problems 
they wrote 
the report however said that despite increased media coverage 
in recent months there has been no upsurge in thefts 
many museum officials may be uncomfortable with other findings 
published in the catalog such as the fact that 575 percent of 
the art works stolen from museums were taken out of storage rooms 
and the thefts were probably inside jobs only 40 percent of the 
works were actually removed from exhibition walls the report said 
stealing works from storage is a very peculiar crime usually 
committed by a guard or office worker not for financial gain but 
usually out of spite or the desire to have a souvenir to keep 
the report said 
the catalog lists the stolen works in alphabetical order 
provides photographs of each work says when and from where it was 
stolen and gives pertinent information on the artist 
the catalog published by the department of national museums and 
the interior ministry is to be updated on a regular basis 
</TEXT>
