<TEXT>
worry about domestic economic 
turmoil and the global crisis of communism is causing authorities 
to get even tougher with dissidents and people they dont trust 
vietnamese and western sources report 
the crackdown has included arrests tightened surveillance and 
suppression of the only legal dissident group the club of former 
resistance fighters at least half a dozen foreigners have been 
detained since april and two americans accused of antigovernment 
activity were deported 
sources said conservatives appeared to have gained the upper 
hand over those in the communist party leadership who favor 
economic and other reforms 
there is a tremendous sense of insecurity in top party 
ranks said a source with access to many officials there is a 
tightening up and everybody is more cautious and afraid to say 
anything they dont acknowledge it but you can see it in their 
faces 
on june 16 hanoi radio said the interior ministry 
counterintelligence force and police in coordination with the 
armed forces had promptly cracked down on many troublemaking and 
sabotage activities 
security forces caught 30 persons violating vietnamese law and 
discovered over 200 foreigners entering the country illegally 
the radio reported 
it said they destroyed five underground reactionary 
organizations and captured tens of their members and seized 
publications with reactionary contents 
many people have taken advantage of international 
organizations investing in vietnam to infiltrate and spy according 
to the broadcast thirty of more than 100 enterprises involved in 
joint ventures with foreign companies were found to be operating 
illegally it said 
hanoi radio said the crackdown was connected with major 
anniversaries an apparent reference to the 15th anniversary april 
30 of victory in the vietnam war and the centenary may 19 of the 
birth of independence leader ho chi minh authorities feared 
protests on both days but none materialized 
sources say dissident activity in vietnam is minimal and the 
actions reflect paranoia over the possible loss of political 
and economic support from the soviet union and eastern europe 
another factor they said was the bold challenge by prodemocracy 
demonstrators last year in china 
a hanoi radio report may 23 claimed the cia had subverted 
eastern europe and was trying to do the same in vietnam by 
circulating leaflets and employing tourists overseas vietnamese 
minority ethnic groups and catholics 
many noncommunist nations halted aid to vietnam after its 
invasion of cambodia in december 1978 
washington also forbids commercial dealings but businessmen 
from other western countries have flocked to vietnam in the 
increasingly open climate of the past two years 
the crackdown appears focused on ho chi minh city a southern 
commercial center that formerly was saigon capital of south 
vietnam 
for the first time in numerous visits to vietnam in recent 
years a reporters papers were searched before his flight left by 
a uniformed man introduced as a cultural officer 
when asked the reason for the search the man merely chuckled a 
government employee who was to help the journalist through customs 
appeared nervous and left early 
two wellconnected sources who demanded anonymity said they 
believed the tightening was temporary and did not mean an end to 
doi moi the communist partys 3yearold economic 
renovation program they added however that it might last 
until a national party congress expected in mid1991 
most of those detained were either close to the party or members 
of it the sources said the hanoi radio report said some 
confused and utopian party members had aided the alleged cia 
sabotage campaign 
an early sign of trouble in the party was tran xuan bachs 
expulsion in march from the ruling politburo after he supported 
greater democracy 
security forces also feared the decentralization of the economy 
and some political affairs had increased public discontent the 
sources reported 
farmers demanding land reform marched in ho chi minh city last 
year it was the first known street demonstrations under communist 
rule 
students have held campus protests of poor conditions at the 
universities 
hundreds of people protested at the city hall demanding 
repayment of money they invested in a perfume company that used 
liberalized rules to create a pyramid scheme 
smuggling corruption and crime have become major issues 
authorities decided the presence of foreigners would complicate 
matters and tightened visa rules in late april a vietnamese 
official said privately 
western businessmen said officials who once pleaded for 
investment had slowed things down and were preoccupied with 
ideological matters 
in interviews with the associated press authorities said there 
were no mass arrests 
no more than 10 vietnamese were arrested with businessman mike 
morrow one of the americans deported said nguyen son vice 
chairman of the information and ideological department in ho chi 
minh city 
gen tran cong man vice president of the vietnamese journalists 
association said there have been no mass arrests but many 
people were warned 
morrow said his interrogators were convinced he was a spy and 
that the united states was trying to create a tiananmen in 
vietnam a reference to the beijing prodemocracy demonstrations 
crushed a year ago 
the american who was held for three weeks before deportation 
said those arrested with him included do trung hieu a respected 
intellectual who belongs to the communist party 
miriam hershberger an american teacher in the capital hanoi 
was deported june 5 for allegedly trying to incite student unrest 
both americans were considered sympathetic to the government as 
was chan tin one of two catholic priests detained in may and 
accused of preaching anticommunism like hieu he was a leader of 
wartime opposition to the usbacked government of south vietnam 
the club of former resistance fighters is made up of southern 
war heroes and revolutionaries who criticize the partys postwar 
performance but have not questioned its leading role 
in march the clubs two leaders were expelled apparently on 
orders from the authorities a source reported he said the club 
approved a resolution in january criticizing the government and 
demanding more political reform 
nguyen son the ho chi minh city party official denied the 
report he said the clubs executive board expelled the leaders 
after they wrote and distributed documents calling for protests 
against the government 
son said one of the men ta ba tang was under temporary 
detention and the other nguyen ho was at home he did not make 
clear whether ho was under restrictions 
a british journalist who reported the clubs actions after 
interviewing tang and other members was detained briefly and 
several of his vietnamese contacts were reported arrested 
