<TEXT>
kiko kawashima is a college student living in a 
small apartment with her parents but come friday japans 
modernday cinderella will call a palace her home 
in japans first royal wedding in six years the 23yearold 
miss kawashima is to wed emperor akihitos youngest son prince 
aya who is 24 and second in line to the chrysanthemum throne 
the wedding will be lavish the government has allotted nearly 
1 million and filled with traditions dating back more than 1000 
years 
but to a nation that only last year buried emperor hirohito 
whose 62year reign spanned a turbulent period of militarist 
expansionism and economic reconstruction the wedding also is being 
hailed as the first taste of a new era 
as far as the clearly smitten japanese media are concerned 
prince aya could not have chosen a better mate than kikosan 
who is only the second commoner to marry into the imperial family 
ayas mother empress michiko became the first in 1959 when she 
married emperor akihito who was then crown prince akihito 
ascended the throne immediately after hirohitos death on jan 7 
1989 
most of japans major television networks will broadcast live 
coverage of the ceremony and related events the wedding is 
scheduled to begin at 10 am and will be followed by several other 
ceremonies so television coverage will likely last well into the 
night 
along with the countless comparisons to cinderella miss 
kawashima has been dubbed the apartment princess because of her 
relatively humble abode faculty housing on the campus of tokyos 
gakushuin university 
at gakushuin miss kawashima is working on her masters degree 
in psychology her father tatsuhiko teaches economics there 
the former peers school boasts much of the imperial family and 
former nobility among its alumni it is where miss kawashima and 
her prince met in 1985 when he too was a gakushuin student 
since the engagement of aya and miss kawashima was formally 
announced in september flocks of reporters often have staked out 
the kawashimas threebedroom apartment 
they have tagged along as miss kawashima did her final 
prewedding shopping and even as she made a rare appearance at a 
bowling alley her score was reportedly about 100 
though the japanese and their media generally treat the monarchy 
with great deference photographing miss kawashimas mother hanging 
the family laundry out to dry is apparently acceptable as is 
broadcasting it to millions of television viewers 
aya who returned thursday from two years of zoology studies at 
englands oxford university has managed to avoid most of the media 
blitz 
palace officials say the somber 15minute wedding will begin 
with the sound of shrill classical japanese music the young 
couple attended by several chamberlains will slowly walk down a 
corridor to a wooden shrine at the imperial palace 
after aya makes his vows to the sun goddess amaterasu from whom 
legend says the imperial family descended the couple will sip rice 
wine to seal their marital bond 
later in the day they are to visit akihito and michiko to 
announce their marriage in keeping with tradition the emperor and 
empress will not be among the guests invited to the ceremony itself 
the guest list however does include such dignitaries as prime 
minister toshiki kaifu and the heads of the judicial and 
legislative branches of government 
the emperor is to bestow upon aya a new title to mark his 
marriage and creation of an independent household ayas given name 
is fumihito but japanese only rarely refer to him by that 
following three days of receptions and three more days to rest 
aya and miss kawashima will travel to the grand shrines of ise the 
central place of worship for believers of shinto japans 
indigenous religion 
before returning to tokyo where they will pay their respects at 
hirohitos mausoleum they also will visit the tomb dedicated to 
japans first emperor jimmu who according to legend began his 
reign in 660 bc 
police plan to mobilize 9000 officers to guard against leftist 
attacks and the public will have little chance to see the royal 
couple in person 
but a short parade from the imperial palace to the akasaka 
palace where the emperor and empress reside is planned 
