<TEXT>
the assembled schoolchildren 
hailed the declaration of the year of peace by tossing skyward 
50 doves 
the birds which had been too tightly clutched through hours of 
delayed ceremonies and president alfredo cristianis speech 
flapped and flailed and crashed to ungainly landings on the 
national legislatures parking lot 
but they eventually limbered their cramped wings they took 
flight 
like the schoolchildrens flock in the june 1 ceremony the 
difficult negotiating process intended to end 10 years of civil war 
in el salvador has also had a tough time getting off the ground 
but government and guerrilla negotiators on monday ended a week 
of talks in mexico that the un mediator said produced 
unprecedented movement both sides expressed guarded optimism that 
next months round could produce concrete accords to pave the way 
for a ceasefire before the years end 
the obstacles to a settlement are daunting and the climb is 
steeply uphill four efforts at negotiating peace between 1984 and 
1989 broke down over mutual recriminations of intransigence 
yet perhaps for the first time in the war both sides appear 
definitively convinced that military resolution of the conflict is 
impossible and that there is no alternative to goodfaith 
negotiation 
its the old question of whether the glass is half empty or 
half full said guerrilla negotiator salvador samayoa i prefer 
to see it as half full and not because of mere optimism but 
because conditions favor movement toward peace 
in november the rebels launched their biggest offensive of the 
war trying to spark insurrection that would topple the government 
failing that the offensive was designed to leave the insurgents 
entrenched in urban positions from which they could demand and 
obtain an expeditious negotiated solution 
the huge push was beaten back after three weeks the product of 
many months of preparation the offensive failed to define the 
wars outcome 
for its part the government is being nudged toward a negotiated 
solution by a combination of factors 
the guerrilla offensive although ultimately unsuccessful 
showed the military the rebels remain strong and motivated 
cristianis republican nationalist alliance wants to do well in 
legislative and municipal elections scheduled for march and 
expects the mantle of peacemaker would produce significant 
electoral dividends 
perhaps most important the us government that has funded the 
nearly bankrupt government and war effort has served notice it will 
not continue providing large sums merely to maintain the status quo 
the unmediated peace process addresses a sevenpoint agenda 
the top item of which is the future role of the armed forces the 
talks eventual success hinges on accord on that subject by far 
the most difficult 
el salvador is a small volcanostudded nation of 5 million on 
the pacific coast of central america notorious throughout its 
history for lopsided distribution of wealth 
the armed forces were for most of this century the key factor in 
ensuring that the few rich got richer while the many poor remained 
so 
relatively progressive younger officers staged a coup in 1979 
with the stated intention of modernizing and democratizing the 
country but the reform movement assailed on one side by oldline 
rightist officers degenerated into a bloody conflict with rebels 
wanting revolutionary change 
an estimated 72000 people most of them civilians have been 
killed in the war 
the farabundo marti national liberation front a leftist 
insurgent army of about 7000 fulltime combatants and perhaps 
twice as many parttime militia members is battling a usfunded 
force of 56000 soldiers and militarized police 
the fmln contends that despite periodic elections and democratic 
trappings the government is a civilian facade on military 
dictatorship 
though government officials describe el salvador as a fledgling 
democracy the armed forces enjoy a degree of power and privelege 
uncountenanced by any modern democratic system 
the rebels demand demilitarization of salvadoran society 
shafik handal leader of the rebel delegation in mexico said 
demilitarization includes disappearance of the insurgent army 
but before the guerrillas demobilize they demand first of all 
an end to military impunity 
although international rights organizations blame the armed 
forces for the slaying outside of combat of many thousands of 
suspected opponents not a single officer has been convicted or 
even tried for a rights abuse crime 
handal and other guerrilla chiefs acknowledge that trial and 
conviction of all or even most offenders is utopian and have 
centered demands for prosecution on four exemplary cases 
the rebels say identification of those responsible for egregious 
abuses and their administrative removal from positions of command 
would suffice as punishment for those implicated in crimes other 
than the four symbolic cases 
in addition to the purge the rebels demand abolishment of 
militarized police forces they consider repressive and creation of 
a new police force under civilian command and control 
agreements on the dismantling of paramilitary organizations 
drastic reduction in the number of military personnel and an end to 
forced recruitment are also rebel conditions for giving up the 
armed struggle 
oscar santamaria chief of the government delegation to the 
mexican talks told the associated press that the discussions 
produced advances that could pave the way for accords at the next 
round 
among elements contributing to chances for successful 
negotiations 
the united states supports the removal of tainted and corrupt 
officers government officials privately concur that once the war 
is over police forces should be under a civilian portfolio rather 
than the defense ministry 
and cristiani has pledged to significantly reduce military 
strength once peace is achieved 
if the military stumbling blocks are overcome the other issues 
human rights judicial and electoral reform constitutional 
revision and economic accords could follow relatively easily 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note douglas grant mine has covered el salvador for 
the associated press since 1987 
</TEXT>
