<TEXT>
the writer recently spent a week traveling in 
rebelheld areas of liberia 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a grisly sign of civil war stands at the 
shattered center of this remote liberian town the skull of a 
government soldier his scalp and half his face withering in the 
relentless sun 
the head is impaled on a stake near a gutted armored personnel 
carrier that residents say was one of two that burst into town 
before dawn april 1 
rebels said they shot out the six tires of the vehicle bearing 
the markings of the liberian armys 1st battalion infantry and 
immolated the halfdozen soldiers inside with firebombs 
surrounding buildings are riddled with bullet holes and the dirt 
road is still littered with empty cartridges survivors say about 
60 of kpaytuos 1000 residents were killed by marauding soldiers 
of the widely hated military of president samuel k doe 
it is the kind of carnage that could resume with the collapse of 
peace talks this week between representatives of doe and charles 
taylor leader of the national patriotic front rebels 
burnedout or abandoned villages destroyed automobiles and 
looted homes and shops dot the inhospitable liberian interior the 
violence is part of the 6monthold war between the rebels 
primarily of the gio and mano ethnic groups and mandingos and the 
krahns who support doe a krahn 
there have been many clashes in the country and we are 
suffering said thomas karngbeae a high school history teacher 
in kpaytuo whose best friend was killed they come to the 
villages to harrass and kill innocent people 
in nearby bahn 125 miles from the atlantic coast the area 
around the towns center crossroads was flattened and burned 
most of our brothers and sisters were killed by does soldiers 
fumes peter vaye bahns deputy military police commander 
the krahn soldiers burned our food storerooms so we are 
suffering for food says vaye his white clothes filthy with 
grime dozens of people were killed he says 
karnue an 85yearold farmer wearing a tattered blue smock 
remembers when the soldiers came to town that night in early april 
they just drove in and burned houses he said he said four of 
his children died in the raid 
taylor a former doe administration official led his insurgent 
forces into liberia in december from neighboring ivory coast the 
rebels are within 15 miles of monrovia and say they can seize the 
capital in 12 hours 
rebel spies are helping prepare the attack says commander bobby 
hayes chief of rebel intelligence our men traveled to monrovia 
and went downtown we see there is very little to stop us 
if ordered to attack we can take monrovia in a day says 
tiagen wantee the fronts deputy battle group commander for the 
port of buchanan who says he was trained by green berets in the 
united states and the special antiterrorism unit in israel we 
did not start this war to stay in buchanan 
the guerrillas are trained in gborplay a northern liberian 
village scraped out of the rain forest near the border with ivory 
coast 
by day the people of gborplay work in nearby fields of corn 
rice and cassava a potatolike tuber as wild parrots whistle and 
chatter overhead 
they return home before nightfall there is no electricity 
when the fireflies come out among coffee bushes and jungle beasts 
begin their haunting calls from the surrounding jungle 
atrocities by does soldiers have galvanized the largely gio and 
mano population of the north tales abound of doe soldiers tying 
women and children to mattresses and setting them on fire 
sam belleh a mano who trains rebel guerrillas in gborplay says 
he saw government soldiers murder his friends wife who was eight 
months pregnant they cut her open and took out the baby the 
baby was stabbed many times i couldnt stand the sight and fled in 
the bush 
soldiers also threw young children into wells belleh said he 
thinks about 800 were killed in that december attack at saclepea 
also in the north 
commando trainees most barefoot are put through exercises by 
john teah 29 a deputy training commander 
teah in combat fatigues and wearing a large brass cross around 
his neck also leads daily sessions of a beautiful chorus half 
african ballad half us marine corps drill chants 
everywhere we go people want to know who we are sing 
several hundred recruits marching in place so we tell them we 
are special commandos marching to the towns 
rebel recruits include 12yearold anthony slersue who carries 
a loaded machine gun slung from his shoulder he says his older 
sister and brother were killed by the liberian army 
christopher nyeneken 14 a mano from sannequellie is learning 
to be a guerrilla to free liberia and because they killed my 
father 
but life in the camp is tough one young teenager tugged at a 
visitors sleeve saying sir we are hungry 
their inexperience can have tragic consequences during the 
battle for buchanan last month daniel zuu was reaching for a 
machine gun reloaded by a 12yearold when the youngster 
accidentally pulled the trigger nearly emptying the magazine into 
zuus elbow 
zuu 40 lost his left arm but says that wont keep him from 
the war front i will never retreat he says stubbornly i 
will never surrender 
