<TEXT>
the nations broiler belt hasnt changed much 
over the years but the agriculture department says production is 
spilling over into other states 
for example oklahoma and missouri more than doubled the 
number of broilers they raised from 1980 to 1989 reflecting a 
spillover from adjoining arkansas a report said other states 
raising more broilers include tennessee south carolina and 
pennsylvania 
but the broiler industry is still concentrated in 10 states 
which accounted for 83 percent of the us output last year most 
are in the south which produced 48 billion birds in 1989 or 87 
percent of the total 
arkansas was the leader with about 920 million broilers last 
year followed by georgia with 812 million and alabama with 750 
million 
others states in the top 10 include north carolina mississippi 
texas maryland delaware california and virginia 
the report by lee christensen and agnes perez of the udsas 
economic research service was included in the july issue of 
agricultural outlook magazine 
although some of this spillover does not reflect major 
regional production shifts further growth in traditional broiler 
areas is becoming increasingly constrained by environmental and 
economic pressures the report said high concentrations of 
broilers result in increasingly complex problems associated with 
waste management water quality and animal disease 
also as city sprawl develops near major broiler production 
centers land prices and labor costs rise thus adding to operating 
costs 
areas with underemployed resources lighter population 
densities and fewer environmental pressures sometimes offer 
financial and other incentives to attract broiler complexes the 
report said 
broiler production grew from 37 billion pounds readytocook 
weight in 1960 to 173 billion pounds in 1989 this years output 
is estimated at 186 billion pounds 
industry development in the broiler belt was pushed by local 
entrepreneurs and aided by the readily available and relatively 
lowcost work force the report said in addition a warm 
climate helped reduce energy costs while growers used improved 
production technologies that adapted well to the south 
as production grew a large infrastructure of support developed 
including slaughter and processing plants 
the report said a 1989 industry survey of the 52 largest broiler 
companies showed that the largest four accounted for 45 percent of 
the total volume through 76 slaughter and further processing 
plants 
the survey also found that the top eight companies accounted for 
about 60 percent of the volume in 105 plants and that the largest 
20 firms had 80 percent of the volume in 156 plants 
approximately 75 percent of the slaughter plants surveyed were 
in the top 10 broiler states the report said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
wind erosion eased its grip on the great 
plains this season because of improved moisture conditions in much 
of the region according to a final survey by the agriculture 
department 
wilson scaling chief of the departments soil conservation 
service said tuesday that an estimated 78 million acres were 
damaged by wind in the 10 states that make up the great plains 
down 45 percent from 143 million acres in 198889 
the agency measures wind damage during a sevenmonth season that 
runs from nov 1 through may 31 when winds are usually the 
strongest and soils the driest the survey covers 541 counties in 
the 10 states 
most of this decrease is the result of precipitation in 
colorado and kansas where land damaged from wind decreased from 
65 million acres last year to 463000 acres this year for the two 
states scaling said 
the greatest damage was in north dakota in its third year of 
severe drought he said the state reported 29 million acres 
damaged this season compared with 23 million last year and a 
record 35 million acres in 198788 
north dakota accounted for more than onethird of the total wind 
erosion in the 10state region 
kansas after setting a record with 51 million acres damaged 
last year largely because of a oneday storm that damaged nearly 
48 million acres reported only 190000 acres damaged this season 
the least damage was in nebraska with 130000 acres damaged 
compared with 192000 last year 
officials said the record for land damaged by wind in the great 
plains was 153 million acres in 195455 the year that the agency 
began annual records 
according to the survey the statebystate breakdown comparing 
winddamaged acres in 198990 with damage in 198889 included 
colorado 273731 and 1403655 
kansas 189600 and 5126250 
montana 1249665 and 1832025 
nebraska 130115 and 191605 
new mexico 248500 and 117950 
north dakota 2932687 and 2297681 
