<TEXT>
just as in the american civil rights movement 
a quarter century ago the question of violence versus nonviolence 
in a struggle for human rights hung over nelson mandelas visit to 
washington 
the black south african leader received a thunderous ovation 
after a speech to a joint session of congress on tuesday a 
reception that left him pausing in the aisle afterward to wave to 
members of congress and the crowded gallery 
behind him a white republican rep chris shays of connecticut 
slapped high fives with black congressmen 
rep john lewis a democrat from georgia couldnt help but feel 
a bit of astonishment at the scene lewis is a veteran of the civil 
rights struggle of the 1960s who remained dedicated to nonviolence 
despite 40 arrests and vicious attacks during the freedom rides and 
elsewhere 
his last arrest lewis recalled after mandelas speech was in 
january 1966 outside the south african information center in new 
york city he and other members of the student nonviolent 
coordinating committee were protesting south africas apartheid 
system and its imprisonment of mandela 
i never thought id live to see nelson mandela out of jail 
lewis said 
