<TEXT>
nasa says it will run a fuel test on 
space shuttle atlantis on thursday to assure itself the rest of the 
shuttle fleet does not have hydrogen leaks like the one that has 
grounded columbia 
we believe that we dont have a generictype of a flaw that 
should indict the rest of the hardware in the fleet jack boykin 
deputy manager of johnson space centers orbiter projects office 
said tuesday 
we want to prove that to ourselves beyond any reasonable doubt 
because there is a potential safety hazard to having a hydrogen 
leak 
columbia has been grounded by a tiny fuel leak that forced nasa 
to scrub its mission may 30 six hours before liftoff hydrogen is 
highly combustible the shuttle was to have carried the 150 
million astro observatory 
the leak is in the area where the orbiter is connected to the 
big external fuel tank it is thought to be in a valve on the 
orbiter nasa said 
up to 200000 gallons of supercold liquid hydrogen will be 
pumped into atlantis external tank on thursday about half the 
tanks capacity to test its valve the same test helped nasa 
locate generally the leak in columbia 
its unclear whether nasa will launch atlantis on a secret 
military mission in midjuly if the exact cause of columbias 
problems have not been determined by then 
boykin said there are still folks in our community who arent 
committed to that yet the subject will be discussed during a 
flight readiness review on thursday and friday he said a launch 
date will then be announced 
in repairs on columbia a 17inchdiameter valve that carries 
liquid hydrogen from the external tank to the main engine was 
removed from the tank side but no leaks were found the problem 
consequently lies on the orbiter side and the valve from the 
unfinished shuttle endeavour will replace the bad component nasa 
said 
there is only one such valve on the orbiter side of the shuttle 
the valve on the external tank side is jettisoned along with the 
tank minutes after liftoff and a new valve accompanies every new 
tank 
columbias hydrogen lines indicated leakage during a mechanical 
test in 1984 to check the valve on the external tank side boykin 
said seven other valves including the one on atlantis also 
failed at that time 
the valve on the external tank side of columbia and the others 
that failed underwent yet another check each valve passed that 
test boykin said 
thirtythree of 64 valves made from 1980 to 1986 when the 
challenger explosion temporarily halted production leaked hydrogen 
during the mechanical test boykin said seventeen were within 
acceptable limits he said 
the remaining 16 went through the second test and passed boykin 
said nine went on to fly and performed well he said 
a similar test was performed with the valves on the orbiter side 
of the shuttles and no problems were detected boykin said 
the valve that apparently is leaking on columbia was modified 
following the challenger accident and has flown twice without any 
problems he said 
