<TEXT>
plans for political union of a dozen west 
european countries have moved ahead but its still unclear what 
the final product will look like 
leaders of the european community wrapped up a twoday summit on 
tuesday by agreeing to open a special conference on dec 14 to 
sketch in the details 
british prime minister margaret thatcher is confident she has 
scotched grandiose plans for some kind of federal europe 
i think we have won on that she told reporters 
irish prime minister charles haughey host of the summit said 
the leaders wanted to have a new closer much more integrated 
political relationship 
there will be he said a much closer growing together 
politically 
some have suggested the community should turn itself into a 
federal united states of europe 
others predict a more limited outcome 
they foresee closer cooperation in foreign policy areas so the 
community can play a more influential role on the world stage 
the european parliament the communitys legislature likely 
would be strengthened it would have more say over the european 
commission the trading blocs executive body 
mrs thatcher has opposed any moves that would transfer national 
sovereignty to new community agencies 
to sharpen the debate aides of the leaders have drawn up a list 
of questions that need to be answered before a political union can 
be formed 
the fivepage document said the overall goal is to strengthen 
the ability of the governments to act in the areas of their 
common interests 
the unity and coherence of its policies and actions should be 
ensured through strong and democratic institutions it said 
the paper asked whether new powers should be transferred to the 
community from individual governments it wondered how the notion 
of community citizenship should be dealt with and whether new 
agencies should be set up 
the paper was drawn up after the leaders committed themselves at 
an arpil summit also held in dublin to a political merger by late 
1992 
their decision was sparked by the political upheavals in eastern 
europe the west european nations contend they must offer stability 
at a time of uncertainty in eastern europe 
the special conference on political union will run parallel to a 
convention starting dec 13 on fashioning an economic and 
monetary union 
the conferences are needed to change the communitys founding 
treaty of rome and set up any new political or monetary agencies 
officials want both conferences to finish their work and the 
nations to ratify any treaty changes by late 1992 
that is the date when the nations already are set to create a 
europeanwide market to do that they intend to get rid of the 
many trade barriers that bar the free movement of money people and 
products 
