<TEXT>
a state court today convicted a 
49yearold west german industrialist of helping build a poison gas 
plant in libya and sentenced him to five years in prison 
juergen hippenstielimhausen was found guilty of violating 
export laws and tax evasion for his involvement in construction of 
the widely publicized plant in the libyan city of rabta south of 
tripoli 
hippenstielimhausen admitted at his trial earlier this month 
that he helped build the chemical plant while he headed the 
imhausenchemie company of lahr a southwestern city near mannheim 
the prosecution had asked for a prison term of 6 years for 
hippenstielimhausen calling him a merchant of death he had 
faced a maximum sentence of eight years 
defense lawyers sought a briefer sentence noting that the 
defendant had confessed judge juergen henninger sentenced him to 
five years 
the ruling followed an 11day trial one of the most heavily 
publicized business trials in west german history 
hippenstielimhausen said in court on june 13 that he had 
suspicions the project would be in conflict with west germanys 
export laws but did not investigate because he didnt want to 
lose the business 
west german law forbids the export of technology or material 
that could be used in conflict areas such as the middle east 
libya has said the rabta plant was intended for producing 
pharmaceuticals but us and west german officials have said it 
was built to manufacture chemical weapons 
hippenstielimhausen testified that the rabta project began in 
1984 when a middleman contacted him about building a chemical 
plant to make pharmaceuticals and insecticides 
he said he found out later that the 136 million project was to 
be in libya and that his participation might violate west german 
law 
hippenstielimhausen also admitted not paying taxes on 117 
million on profits from his transactions 
allegations that several western companies helped build the 
rabta plant have triggered worldwide debate about toughening 
international export law enforcement 
hippenstielimhausen is the only person to be charged in the 
case though west german authorities are investigating 18 other 
people 
imhausenchemie was found to be the key supplier of equipment 
construction plans and technical expertise to develop the rabta 
project prosecutor hansheiko klein said hippenstielimhausen had 
delivered plans and documents as well as providing material valued 
at 12 million 
the defendant was arrested in may 1989 and kept in investigative 
custody since his time in custody counts toward his sentence 
on tuesday the ard television network said libya intended to 
build a second plant using the plans furnished by 
hippenstielimhausen for the first plant it cited us and west 
german intelligence sources for the information 
the television report said two west german companies and a 
netherlands firm were suspected of having ties to the project 
according to the report the stuttgart prosecutors office is 
investigating the allegations against the companies in west germany 
the libyan scandal first came to light in december 1988 when 
the united states charged that west german firms were providing 
massive assistance for construction of a chemical factory capable 
of producing poison gas 
west german government officials at first denied any of the 
countrys companies were involved but later acknowledged the 
allegations were true 
