<TEXT>
communist party officials said today that the 
central committee will meet friday to consider postponing next 
weeks party congress a policysetting gathering of 4700 
delegates from across the country 
reformers fear that conservative foes of president mikhail s 
gorbachevs could dominate the gathering split the party and 
undermine the soviet leader as he tries to pull his country out of 
a deep economic and political crisis 
the congress scheduled months ago is to begin monday but 
reports suddenly surfaced this week that it might be put off 
because of concerns that hardliners may prevail 
the reformminded president of the russian republic boris n 
yeltsin told a news conference tuesday that he favored postponing 
the congress until autumn to stabilize the political situation 
a party official who spoke on condition of anonymity said today 
that partys 249member policymaking central committee would meet 
on friday 
yeltsin predicted there would be a real struggle at the 
central committee plenum over the congress timing 
a postponement could prevent party hardliners from capitalizing 
on their successes last week at a meeting of party members from the 
russian federation the largest soviet republic 
the 2700 party members at the russian federation meeting will 
constitute a majority of delegates to the national congress 
party congresses are normally held every five years delegates 
have the right to elect the party leadership and change the partys 
rules and program though in the past power has always flowed from 
the top 
until gorbachev came to power the party was the countrys 
leading political force now gorbachev has stripped it of its 
political monopoly as he seeks to transfer power to a more 
democratic government 
the communists have been blamed for the sorry state of the 
economy and have suffered major defeats at the polls 
gorbachev heads both the party as general secretary and the 
government as president a post whose powers he has expanded so he 
could lose the party post and still be soviet leader 
despite the uncertainty surrounding the congress the central 
committee went ahead today and published a program statement 
that the congress will discuss and be asked to approve 
the program spread across almost two pages of the communist 
party daily pravda takes a repentant tone about the partys blame 
for the countrys ills 
but it maintains that the countrys main problem lay in the past 
distortion of socialism not the ideology itself 
false ideas about socialism as a society based on the state 
monopoly on property and dictatorship led by the partystate brass 
in the name of the proletariat led to tyranny and lawlessness and 
the alienation of people from property and authority the 
committee said 
the program backs many of gorbachevs reforms already under way 
including the transition to a market economy and the partys 
rejection of its former political monopoly 
it also proposes more independence for party organizations in 
the 15 soviet republics and allows for the possibility of various 
platforms in the party without actually approving fullfledged 
factions 
on the issue of whether party units should be removed from the 
kgb and army the program says the party groups should be allowed 
to remain but be clearly separate from the basic power structure 
the russian federations parliament gave preliminary approval 
this month to a decree that would ban the party units in the kgb 
and army it also forbade officials to combine a high party and 
government post 
yeltsin said tuesday that the national party congress was the 
last chance for radical renewal of the party and that he would 
suspend his party membership if he is dissatisfied with the results 
the public debate over whether to postpone the congress 
contrasted sharply with carefully orchestrated meetings in the past 
along with the new program gorbachev is trying to bring new 
party rules to this congress according to an early draft they 
would slim down the central committee and expand the ruling 
politburo which has generally included about a dozen members and 
done all the partys most important decisionmaking 
it would also be renamed the presidium 
gorbachevs spokesman arkady a maslennikov asked tuesday by 
reporters about gorbachevs position on the congress timing 
declined to comment and said the central committee would decide 
when the congress would be held 
