<TEXT>
prime minister margaret thatcher today urged an 
international conference to reduce the use of chemicals depleting 
the ozone layer and she pledged 9 million to the worlds first 
global environmental fund 
we need to speed up action and set ourselves higher targets 
and shorter deadlines for reducing and eventually eliminating cfcs 
and halons mrs thatcher told the government ministers and 
officials from nearly 100 countries 
even if all the chemicals which damage the ozone layer were 
banned tomorrow ozone depletion would continue to get worse for 
more than a decade it would still take our planet well beyond the 
lifetime of all of us here to replenish the ozone already lost 
that is the extent of the damage we have already done 
cfcs used in aerosol sprays refrigerators foams and cleaning 
solvents destroy ozone gas scattered through the stratosphere 
about 30 to 50 miles above the earths surface scientists say that 
without the gas that filters out harmful ultraviolet rays life in 
earth would cease 
higher ultraviolet radiation damages the human immune system 
causes skin cancer and cataracts harms crops and disrupts sea life 
dr mostafa tolba executive director of the un environment 
program told delegates far too much is at stake to contemplate 
failure we have no option but to succeed and inshallah god 
willing we will succeed 
tolba said the london meeting was establishing a new political 
movement to deal with the environmental crisis a movement rooted 
in respect for the value of human life the value of nature we are 
not just writing a new treaty we are writing a new chapter in 
international relations 
during the threeday meeting the officials will study proposals 
calling for a worldwide ban on a group of chemicals that threaten 
the planets ozone shield the conference also will discuss a 
proposal to create an international fund to help poorer countries 
pay the high price for ozonefriendly technology 
conference sources said diplomats were close to agreement on 
such a fund which the united states opposed until two weeks ago 
in a week of working sessions before the meeting moved to 
ministerial level delegates tried to hammer out details for the 
fund proposal 
but a number of tricky issues remain to be resolved by the 
ministers including where the funds will come from 
many developing countries insist that the richer industrialized 
nations help the third world pay the bill estimated at 2 to 7 
billion in the coming years for converting to substitutes for 
chloroflurocarbons or cfcs 
developed nations led by the united states want to shift their 
contributions from aid funds already allocated 
the ministers appear likely to agree on a threeyear down 
payment of 160 million as suggested by tolba 
another 80 million would be promised to china and india to 
coax them into signing the 1987 montreal protocol on protecting the 
ozone layer 
the ministers work if successful will extend and strengthen 
the montreal protocol already considered an environmental 
watershed 
in september 1987 56 nations agreed to halve cfc by 1996 
since then scientific evidence on the destruction caused by the 
chemicals has prompted countries to move more quickly to eliminate 
them completely eightyone nations decided in principle last year 
to ban them by the year 2000 
ministers will be debating whether to quicken the pace the 
12nation european community along with the nordic countries 
australia and new zealand wants to move up the ban to 1997 the 
united states and japan are opposed 
the ministers are likely to agree to ban halons and carbon 
tetrachloride in addition to cfcs by the year 2000 both are used 
in firefighting 
scientific studies overwhelmingly show the ozone layer will not 
be fully restored unless all the severely damaging chemicals are 
banned worldwide and some of the less harmful substitutes are 
strictly controlled 
