a rebel statement claimed hundreds of buildings had been set 
on fire by incendiaries and that civilians were killed in the raids 
at least 1626 combatants have died since the civil war flared 
up anew on june 11 fighting started after a tamil man claimed he 
was manhandled by sinhalese police and tamil tiger guerrillas 
responded by attacking police stations in the east 
ethnic sinhalese make up 75 percent of the islands 16 million 
people and control the army and the government tamils comprise 18 
percent 
claiming discrimination by the sinhalese tamil tigers have 
since 1983 been waging war to carve out a separate tamil homeland 
in the north and east 
military officials say they believe tamil tiger guerrillas are 
moving into the south and planning attacks against sinhalese 
civilians as retribution for rebel losses in the north and east 
in the past rebel statements have said they kill sinhalese 
civilians because government troops kill tamil civilians 
police and troops today cordoned off kochchikade town about a 
half mile north of colombos city center and went into homes 
shops and businesses questioning young tamils 
residents contacted by telephone said security forces prevented 
people from leaving or entering the town for more than six hours a 
large number of young tamils who were new to the area were taken 
away in police vehicles residents said 
similar operations according to military and police officials 
were being conducted throughout the south with hundreds of tamil 
youths taken into custody 
the worst rebel attack on civilians occurred on may 14 1985 
when a marauding gang of tamil rebels launched a machinegun and 
grenade attack on sinhalese buddhists worshiping at a shrine in 
anuradhapura an ancient capital about 100 miles north of colombo 
in all 157 people were kiled 
military officials say the fighting in the east has tamil rebels 
on the run on tuesday air force helicopters dropped thousands of 
leaflets over a dense jungle asking rebels to surrender 
the leaflets were dropped near kundikudicharu village in the 
eastern batticaloa district where military officials believe 2500 
rebels were trapped 
rebels were asked to leave their weapons behind and come out of 
the jungle the leaflets said the rebels would not be harmed 
