<TEXT>
sticking to the fast track toward 
unification west germany has drawn up a plan to complete its 
merger with the east in december but east germans are already 
feeling the pinch of economic union 
five days before the two countries create one economy east 
germans are being forced to search for food and other necessities 
theres no soap here no meat said ines kroll a 
25yearold mother of two as she pushed her shopping cart past 
depleted shelves in the only store in blankenburg a small town 
north of berlin 
merchants are shutting stores and clearing shelves to make room 
for the expected deluge of western goods groceries have been 
canceling their orders with east german suppliers and letting their 
stocks run out 
experts say many east german companies are keeping their 
products off the market until next week when they can sell them 
for west german marks 
some merchants say they also want to avoid taking in large 
amounts of east german marks in the days before the nearly 
worthless currency is replaced by the valuable west german mark 
in munich a huge west german electronics and household 
appliance company siemens today announced it will invest 600 
million in east germany and hire up to 30000 people in the next 
several years 
the announcement represents the biggest single investment 
program since east germany shed its communist government and began 
moving to a free market 
the east german government on tuesday announced temporary import 
tariffs to protect industries threatened by the switch to 
capitalism after 40 years of socialist central planning 
amid criticism that the rapid merger was hurting many east 
germans west german finance minister theo waigel said that quick 
unification was important because of the unstable situation in the 
soviet union 
we need to go through the door to unification because it can 
close shut again he told reporters 
germans fear instability in eastern europe if soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev should be removed from power in the squeeze 
between hardliners upset with his reforms and progressives who 
think he is moving too slowly 
about 380000 soviet troops are still on east german soil and 
moscow has balked at withdrawing them over objections to natos 
desire that a united germany be party of the western military 
alliance 
suggestions for what a political treaty unifying east and west 
would look like were released tuesday by the west german interior 
ministry in the form of a discussion paper 
under the proposals east germany would officially join west 
germany the day after elections for a joint german parliament 
west and east german politicians have proposed dec 9 or dec 16 
as possible dates for the balloting 
west german interior minister wolfgang schaeuble said in bonn 
west germany on tuesday that he expected the east german cabinet to 
decide today to begin negotiations on the political treaty he said 
a pact should be ready for debate in both parliaments by early 
september 
last week the parliaments of both states ratified the treaty 
outlining the monetary economic and social union that is to take 
effect on sunday 
on that day the west german mark officially replaces the east 
german mark and 40 years of rigid socialist economic policy give 
way to freemarket rules 
lines of up to 1000 people have been snaking down sidewalks in 
east berlin as people converge on banks to fill out paperwork 
necessary for converting savings accounts to west german marks 
depending on age accounts up to 6000 marks 3600 can be 
converted at the most favorable rate of one west german mark for 
each east german mark 
in an attempt to protect its ailing industries from the first 
rush of western competition east germany on tuesday announced a 
series of tariffs on western goods beginning sunday 
an 11 percent tariff is to be imposed through the end of the 
year replaced the following quarter by a 6 percent tariff 
food will not be affected although east germanys huge farm 
collectives are expected to be battered by western agricultural 
producers 
it was uncertain whether the tariffs would remain if the current 
quick pace of unification continues and the nations fully unify in 
december 
many stores are already stocking west german goods under 
agreements made in march that allowed a limited entry of some 
products into the country 
but many staples still were in short supply mrs kroll said she 
could find no detergent and rejected the skimpy selection of meat 
she also had mixed feelings about the end of the east german mark 
my husband mints east german coins for a living she said 
some experts say 1 million to 4 million workers will lose their 
jobs in the first two years of economic unification 
many of the heavy industries that were once the backbone of the 
former centrally planned economy are expected to fail as they face 
leaner more efficient western concerns 
