<TEXT>
the supreme court today limited the power of 
environmentalists to use the federal courts to prevent opening of 
federal lands to commercial development 
by a 54 vote the justices overturned a proenvironmentalist 
ruling that had been challenged by the bush administration 
justice antonin scalia writing for the court said the national 
wildlife federation failed to provide enough or the right kind of 
evidence to justify its suit against the interior department 
the federation challenged the departments plans to change the 
status of some 180 million acres of public land in the west and 
alaska more than a fourth of all public lands in the nation 
the federation said it was suing to protect federal lands 
against unwise or premature disposition and development 
including millions of acres to be opened up to mining and mineral 
leasing 
the decision to reclassify the land for development and other 
uses was made by the reagan administration in 1985 following a 
policy instituted by thensecretary james g watt in 1981 
the wildlife federation said the reagan administration violated 
federal law by opening the land to development without following 
procedures in the 1976 federal land policy and management act 
flpma 
the us circuit court of appeals here said the federation and 
its 45 million members have legal standing to sue based on 
affidavits by members that they use some of the land for recreation 
for example federation member peggy k peterson said she uses 
land in the south passgreen mountain area of wyoming 
scalia today agreed with the bush administration that the 
federation may not base a wholesale challenge to the interior 
departments reclassification on allegations such a change will 
adversely affect a few people 
challenges must be mounted case by case scalia said unless 
congress changes the law to permit a broader attack or federal 
officials bow to such broader demands by environmentalists 
the casebycase approach is understandably frustrating to 
an organization which has as its objective acrosstheboard 
protection of our nations wildlife and the streams and forests 
that support it he said 
but scalia said it is not up to the courts to come up with 
farreaching solutions when not authorized by law 
until confided to us more sweeping actions are for the other 
branches of government he said 
he was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white sandra day oconnor and anthony m kennedy 
dissenting were justices harry a blackmun william j brennan 
thurgood marshall and john paul stevens 
blackmun in an opinion for all four said the wildlife 
federation presented enough evidence in affidavits by two members 
to warrant a full trial of its suit 
he said todays ruling characterized the federal land management 
program as 1250 or so individual classification decisions but 
blackmun said the majority offers no argument in support of this 
conclusory assertion and i am far from certain that the 
characterization is an accurate one 
the case is lujan vs national wildlife federation 89640 
