<DOCNO> AP900627-0083 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
people charged with child abuse are not always 
entitled to a facetoface confrontation with their young accusers 
the supreme court ruled today 
in a decision expected to make it easier to prosecute suspected 
child abusers the court said the constitution allows for 
exceptions to such potentially traumatic confrontations 
the decisions were announced as the court ended its 198990 
term which included major rulings on abortion the right to die 
flag burning political patronage police efforts to stop drunken 
drivers and prayer groups in public schools 
in a major victory for affirmative action the court today 
upheld federal policies that favor minorities in awarding broadcast 
licenses 
by a 54 vote the justices said the federal communications 
commission policies do not discriminate unlawfully 
the childabuse decision will let states use some techniques to 
protect minors particularly those called to testify against their 
accused abusers from a facetoface courtroom confrontation 
more than half the states have enacted such measures already 
by a 54 vote the justices upheld the childmolesting 
conviction of a maryland daycare center owner even though four 
young children were allowed to testify out of her presence the 
children testified over oneway closedcircuit television 
but by a separate 54 vote the court refused to reinstate an 
idaho womans childabuse conviction thrown out by the states 
highest court because the child did not testify rather a 
pediatrician testified at the trial about his interview with the 
2yearold alleged victim 
writing for the court in the maryland case justice sandra day 
oconnor said where necessary to protect a child witness from 
trauma that would be caused by testifying in the physical presence 
of the defendant at least where such trauma would impair the 
childs ability to communicate the constitutions confrontation 
clause does not prohibit use of a procedure other than a 
facetoface confrontation 
she was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices byron r white harry a blackmun and anthony m kennedy 
justices antonin scalia william j brennan thurgood marshall 
and john paul stevens dissented 
writing for the dissenters scalia said seldom has this court 
failed so conspicuously to sustain a categorical guarantee of the 
constitution against the tide of prevailing current opinion 
the constitutions sixth amendment in part says in all 
criminal prosecutions the accused shall enjoy the right to be 
confronted with the witnesses against him 
though we reaffirm the importance of facetoface 
confrontation with witnesses appearing at trial we cannot say that 
such confrontation is an indispensable element of the sixth 
amendments guarantee of the right to confront ones accusers 
the majority said 
states in recent years increasingly have sought to protect young 
witnesses particularly those testifying in childabuse cases 
the number of such cases is growing more than 22 million 
childabuse reports were filed in 1988 according to the national 
committee for the prevention of child abuse 
testimony by children on closedcircuit tv on videotape 
through oneway mirrors or behind screens has been allowed in some 
criminal cases 
todays decision in the maryland case allows those techniques 
as long as they ensure the reliability of the evidence by 
subjecting it to rigorous adversarial testing 
in other action today the court 
limited the power of environmentalists to use the federal 
courts to prevent opening of federal lands to commercial 
development 
by a 54 vote the justices overturned a proenvironmentalist 
ruling that had been challenged by the bush administration 
upheld arizonas death penalty law in a decision that also 
removes a constitutional shadow from similar laws in idaho and 
montana 
the justices by a 54 vote ruled that the arizona law is valid 
even though judges not juries decide whether a murder was a crime 
for which death can be the punishment 
ruled that most of the nations post offices may ban all 
soliciting on their property 
the justices by a 54 vote said a regulation imposing such a 
blanket ban does not violate freespeech rights 
in a significant ruling on the protections offered by the 
constitutions first amendment the court reinstated the 
convictions of two political activists who solicited contributions 
and distributed literature from the sidewalk outside a post office 
in bowie md 
the justices in 1988 struck down an iowa mans sexualassault 
conviction because two 13yearold girls were allowed to testify 
while shielded from his view by a large screen placed in the 
courtroom between them and the defendant they cited a sixth 
amendment violation 
but the 1988 ruling appeared to leave unanswered whether there 
may be exceptions to the facetoface requirement 
the maryland court of appeals threw out sandra craigs 
conviction saying her 7yearold accuser and three other young 
witnesses wrongly were allowed to testify over closedcircuit tv 
they testified from a room outside the courtroom with only a 
prosecutor and one of mrs craigs lawyers present mrs craig and 
her other lawyer remained in the courtroom where they could watch 
the testimony and talk privately by telephone to the other lawyer 
the state court ruled that mrs craig was entitled to a new 
trial on charges she sexually molested a girl who attended her 
clarksville md daycare center 
she had been sentenced to 10 years in prison for her 1987 
conviction on those charges 
today the nations highest court said the maryland court was 
wrong 
mrs craig also faces charges stemming from the alleged 
molestation of 12 other children who attended the daycare center 
in the idaho case laura lee wright of boise was convicted of 
lewd conduct committed on her daughters who were then 5 and 2 she 
was sentenced to 20 years in prison before the state supreme court 
threw out her conviction 
the state court said the trial judge wrongly allowed a 
pediatrician who had examined the younger girl to testify about 
what she told him the girl did not testify and therefore could 
not be crossexamined by mrs wrights lawyer 
the state court said the pediatricians testimony lacked 
particularized guarantees of trustworthiness because it was not 
taperecorded because he asked leading questions and had a 
preconceived idea of what facts the child should be disclosing 
oconnor joined by the four dissenters in the maryland case 
upheld the state court ruling while not agreeing with how that 
ruling was reached 
given the presumption of inadmissibility accorded accusatory 
hearsay statements we agree with the court below that the state 
has failed to show that the younger daughters incriminating 
statements to the pediatrician possessed sufficient particularized 
guarantees of trustworthiness under the confrontation clause to 
overcome that presumption oconnor said 
the cases are maryland vs craig 89478 and idaho vs wright 
89260 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

