<TEXT>
negotiators at eastwest talks on 
reducing conventional forces in europe agreed today to limit the 
number of tanks and armored combat vehicles each alliance may have 
diplomats said 
agreement on the two weapons categories will speed negotiations 
for an initial agreement at the talks by the end of this year they 
said 
this is a very major step a western diplomat told the 
associated press on condition of anonymity this is the heart of 
the treaty along with artillery these are the chief components of 
ground offensive forces limiting this is one of the major steps in 
which these negotiations will increase stability in europe it is 
certainly one of the key elements 
the breakthrough proposal on tanks and armored combat vehicles 
came from the french and the poles 
the frenchpolish proposal which was adopted by the delegates 
establishes an overall ceiling for armored combat vehicles of 
30000 on each side and a ceiling of 20000 tanks for each side 
it also sets a minimum weight limit of 165 tons for tanks 
regardless of whether they have tracks or wheels one of the more 
contentious issues at the talks has been finding common definitions 
for tanks and other armaments 
the agreement also no longer makes a distinction between armored 
troop carriers and other armored vehicles thus removing a further 
obstacle 
nato and warsaw pact delegates referred to the proposal as a 
package noting the link between definitions and limits on 
numbers and weights 
they said the future treaty text will include a long list of the 
arms they would carry thus classifying all the weapons the two 
sides currently have 
polish chief delegate wlodzimierz konarski told reporters 
earlier this month that this would be unprecedented in eastwest 
relations and that these lists would become the basis for the 
reductions 
according to us estimates the west has 23600 tanks against 
warsaw pacts estimated 52500 nato has about 34025 armored 
combat vehicles and the warsaw pact 59400 according to us 
estimates last year 
the talks on conventional forces in europe are designed to 
reduce troops and nonnuclear weapons of the two alliances from the 
atlantic ocean to the ural mountains the 16 nato and seven warsaw 
pact countries are participating 
both sides hope to have an agreement ready for signing by 
december when leaders from 35 nations including the 23 involved 
in the talks meet in paris 
the other 12 participants are neutral and nonaligned countries 
in europe that would also be affected by reducing tensions on the 
continent 
eastern and western diplomats said there were still many 
outstanding issues to be resolved before a final agreement can be 
signed 
