<DOCNO> AP900627-0094 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
canada as a country is an unnatural union 
less a nation than a grouping of regional entities with vastly 
differing interests and outlooks it always has been difficult to 
govern following the failure of the meech lake constitutional 
accord it may become even harder 
its not a natural state either economically or 
geographically and certainly not culturally constitutional 
expert john d whyte said 
and the one cultural linkage that we did have living under a 
british crown has absolutely disappeared said whyte dean of 
the queens university law school 
is canada impossible to govern 
were about to find out said joseph jockel a specialist in 
canadian studies at st lawrence university in canton ny 
beyond the shortterm squabblings and constitutional theory 
there is a combat between two visions of what canada is and they 
may be incompatible 
the majority of quebecois see canada as binational a pact 
between two nations and two people in which one is quebec and one 
the people of canada jockel said meech was to have addressed 
that 
most english canadians see canada as a country of 10 provinces 
and of one people to which some special characteristics in quebec 
have to be accommodated 
meech really crashed on the rocks of those two visions he 
said 
meech lake was an attempt to gain frenchspeaking quebecs 
signature on canadas 1982 constitution the agreement contained 
five points covering the provinces most important concerns 
including one clause designating quebec a distinct society 
within canada 
the clause had little practical impact but was a symbol of 
enormous importance to the 65 million quebecois who make up about 
25 percent of canadas 26 million people 
other provisions involved a new constitutional amending formula 
some powers over immigration a limit on federal spending authority 
and a voice in appointing supreme court justices 
the measure required ratification by the federal government and 
the legislatures of all 10 provinces it died when newfoundland 
premier clyde wells decided not to put it to a vote and when a 
member of the manitoba assembly managed to delay debate beyond 
saturdays deadline 
the failure of the measure angered and embittered many 
quebecois who view it as a rejection by english canada the long 
debate over the amendment and the numerous reservations by other 
provinces gave rise to increased nationalism in the province 
the geography and history of canada make it difficult to find 
national consensus and in the case of constitutional amendments 
such as meech lake unanimity regional interests are nearly 
impossible to overcome 
british columbia in the far west has much more in common with 
the northwest united states than it does with ontario or quebec 
economically its gaze is as much oriented toward the orient as it 
is eastward to the rest of canada 
in the east the impoverished maritime provinces of 
newfoundland nova scotia prince edward island and new brunswick 
depend to a large extent on fish and on government handouts for 
economic survival 
newfoundland only joined the canadian federation in 1949 and 
many newfoundlanders still talk about going up to canada 
alberta in the west with its rich resources in oil and gas 
feels its political clout is not equivalent to its economic might 
that is one reason it fights so hard for reform of the moribund 
canadian senate 
the prairie provinces of saskatchewan and manitoba have always 
been seen as an agricultural vastness and market for central 
canadas products 
quebec with its historical linguistic and cultural 
differences is clearly distinct from the rest of canada it long 
has felt more comfortable in its close relations with the 
northeastern united states and more recently with ontario than 
with the rest of canada 
just look at the quebec license plates from boston to 
florida one quebec official said noting the french province was 
wholeheartedly behind the uscanadian free trade agreement of a 
year ago 
a common feeling is resentment of central canada and opposition 
to ottawa 
because 62 percent of canadas people live in ontario and 
quebec and because nearly 30 percent of all the people in the 
country live either in toronto montreal or vancouver political 
power has been unbalanced 
and while meech lake frequently was portrayed as french vs 
english canada which it was to some extent it was far more 
complicated 
special treatment for quebec was psychologically unacceptable 
for many english canadians and politically unacceptable for others 
now canada is really going to be tested jockel said we 
can count on quebec putting forth a new agenda even more explicity 
based on the notion of canada as two people 
