<DOCNO> AP900627-0096 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
photographs taken from the 15 billion hubble 
space telescope have not been as good as expected the national 
aeronautics and space administration says 
the problem might be caused by all the lights in the telescopes 
mirror not focusing at the same point nasa officials said they 
scheduled a news conference later today 
the telescope was launched into orbit april 25 aboard the space 
shuttle discovery 
it is designed to study the far reaches of the universe while 
free from the distorting effects of earths atmosphere 
in assessing the hubble space telescopes optical performance 
the orbital verification team conducted a series of focus tests 
nasa said 
the anticipated image quality was not achieved it said 
computer models of the images indicate the source of this lesser 
quality image may be what is called spherical aberration a 
spherical aberration occurs when all the lights in a mirror do not 
focus precisely at the same point 
nasa managers are assessing the cause and determining what the 
scientific implications are the agency said 
</TEXT>
