<TEXT>
riots against increases in food prices and 
zambias oneparty government spread from lusaka to smaller cities 
today and troops herded protesters in one town into a sports 
stadium and held them at gunpoint 
hospital officials said five people died today raising the toll 
to at least 20 in the worst rioting in zambias history health 
officials conceded there could have been many more fatalities in 
barricaded suburbs and shanties without transport or telephones 
on the third day of protests and looting the government 
extended 6 pm6 am curfew to 24 hours 
civilian vigilantes patrolled the streets carrying automatic 
rifles military helicopters flew low overhead and suburban 
storekeepers fired volleys of bullets to defend their wares 
wounding an unknown number of looters 
police officials said widespread looting took place throughout 
the day at the town of kafue 25 miles south of lusaka 
army units later herded scores of looters into a kafue sports 
stadium and held them there at gunpoint the officials said on 
condition of anonymity 
rioting also reportedly broke out late tuesday in the 
mineralrich copperbelt province of this southcentral african 
nation where the government has more than doubled the price of 
corn meal as part of subsidycutting reform 
protesters also demand an end to socialist oneparty rule by 
president kenneth kaunda in the country of 75 million people it 
is the most serious challenge to kuandas rule since he came to 
power in 1964 
police said they had detained more than 550 people 
unconfirmed reports said 12 police officers were illed today 
when a rampaging mob attacked chainama police station east of the 
city center 
the attack if confirmed would bring the death toll since 
monday to 32 doctors in lusaka today said at least 20 people died 
and 190 were wounded in three days of riots 
by noon mobs or police had thrown up makeshift road blocks 
using burned out cars or broken masonry in most suburbs troop 
reinforcements in armored personnel carriers positioned themselves 
at strategic points but did not fire 
the windows of most stores in the downtown shopping district 
have been smashed in one witness said 
police spokesman andrew kaitisha said the arrests in lusaka were 
aimed at finding ringleaders among the thousands of protesters 
who rampaged through most districts of the capital looting stores 
burning flags and chanting antigovernment slogans 
they were arrested for screening and are being interviewed by 
a special police team for find out who the agitators are he said 
there were no immediate details of the extent of unrest on the 
copperbelt but reports said demonstrators clashed with security 
forces at the mining town of kitwe about 225 miles north of lusaka 
the violence was sparked by the june 19 increase in the price of 
corn meal the countrys staple from 279 per 55pound bag to 
656 
the increase was announced as part of an economic reform program 
aimed at reducing government subsidies and making the economy of 
one of africas poorest nations more commercially viable 
it had been recommended by financial agencies and donor nations 
the unrest took on a further political dimension as 
demonstrators mostly from lusakas most impoverished townships and 
shanties demanded kaundas ouster and an end to nearly two decades 
of socialiststyle oneparty rule 
earlier this year kaunda promised to hold a referendum on the 
future of zambias oneparty system but no date has been set for 
the vote 
residents of the lusaka suburb of chilenji said rioters smashed 
their way into a home occupied by kaunda a former school teacher 
and lay preacher before he led his nation to independence from 
british colonial rule in 1964 
the house seen in the past as a symbol of zambias black 
nationalist struggle against the british was extensively damaged 
residents said 
student rioters have also burned the flag of kaundas ruling 
united national independence party 
kaunda 67 has made no official comment on the unrest 
 
</TEXT>
