june 23 
the providence ri journalbulletin on the constitutionality 
of roadside checkpoints 
the fourth amendment protects us from unreasonable searches 
and seizures but what about roadside checkpoints which stop 
passing motorists in an effort to identify and apprehend the small 
minority who are driving under the influence of alcohol are these 
reasonable police procedures or do they violate the constitution 
this past week the supreme court ruled 63 that such 
checkpoints are ligitimate this was a sensible ruling it finally 
clears up a longdisputed legal issue and also provides one more 
weapon in the arsenal of those charged with limiting the highway 
mayhem caused by drunk drivers 
writing for the majority chief justice william rehnquist argued 
that roadside checkpoints meet a threepronged test of 
constitutionality 
first the problem being targeted is unquestionably important 
 
second checkpoints constitute an effective mechanism for 
identifying potentially dangerous drunk drivers 
third checkpoints cause only minor interference with peoples 
liberty 
