<TEXT>
more plays and lower ticket prices are the goals 
of a major new initiative to bring audiences back to broadway 
the plan to stimulate the production of plays in designated 
littleused broadway theaters as well as to reduce ticket prices 
was announced tuesday by members of the broadway theater community 
the project called the broadway alliance was born after months 
of discussion among theater owners producers unions and guilds 
said harvey sabinson head of the league of american theaters and 
producers 
it involves salary royalty and manpower reductions and 
concessions by actors producers theater owners unions and 
suppliers an equality of sacrifice said alan eisenberg 
executive secretary of actors equity association and committee 
chairman of the alliance 
because of these concessions production costs for the plays 
must not exceed 400000 and producers must use certain 
underutilized broadway theaters that capitalization is less than 
half of the usual 800000 to 1 million now required to produce a 
play on broadway 
in return ticket prices will be held to a top price of 24 for 
orchestra seats and 19 and 10 for mezzanine and balcony tickets 
the top ticket price for plays on broadway now ranges from 3750 
for the piano lesson to 50 for cat on a hot tin roof and 
the grapes of wrath 
the plan is aimed at oneset plays with small casts and does not 
apply to musicals 
the broadway community can no longer stand by as many of 
americas finest plays are being produced everywhere but on 
broadway said peter stone head of the dramatists guild most 
of these plays in the face of growing costs and lacking a big 
star a major prize or a lavish production have been relegated to 
regional and offbroadway theaters 
such acclaimed works as driving miss daisy steel 
magnolias frankie and johnny in the clair de lune other 
peoples money and the cocktail hour have achieved national 
recognition and large motion picture contracts while broadway can 
only watch and remember a time no more than 10 years ago when 
every one of these fine plays would have been lighting up broadway 
houses stone said 
broadways three major theater owners the shubert nederlander 
and jujamcyn organizations each have provided theaters for the 
new project the houses include the walter kerr the nederlander 
and either the belasco or lyceum theaters only the kerr is 
currently booked the theaters would be booked on a rotating basis 
the plan will go into effect sept 1 and run for 18 months 
until the end of february 1991 when it will be up for review 
producers wishing to participate would have to apply to the 
alliance for approval 
all personnel working at reduced wages including the actors 
will participate in a profitsharing plan after production costs 
are recouped the productions also will pay no rent to the theaters 
until costs are recouped 
</TEXT>
