<DOCNO> AP900627-0118 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
prohibiting people from soliciting on post 
office property does not violate their right of free speech the 
supreme court said wednesday 
the justices voted 54 to reinstate the convictions of two 
political activists who solicited contributions and handed out 
literature on a sidewalk at the bowie md post office in 1986 
we are grateful the supreme court has recognized our 
customers need for unimpeded access to do business with the postal 
service said post office general counsel harold hughes 
the history of regulation of solicitation in post offices 
demonstrates the reasonableness of the provision here at issue 
justice sandra day oconnor wrote in the courts main opinion 
oconnor chief justice william h rehnquist and justices byron 
r white and antonin scalia said a sidewalk on post office property 
is not a traditional public forum where freespeech rights are 
given enhanced protection 
providing the key fifth vote justice anthony m kennedy said 
there was no need to reach that issue because the disputed 
regulation is a valid one restricting the time place or manner of 
speech not its content 
justices william j brennan thurgood marshall harry a 
blackmun and john paul stevens dissented saying such a sidewalk is 
a traditional public forum and that the postal regulation is being 
enforced in a discriminatory way 
marsha kokinda and kevin pearl were arrested outside the bowie 
post office aug 6 1986 after they refused to stop their 
activities from a table they had set up on a sidewalk adjacent to 
the building 
the two are volunteers for the national democratic policy 
committee the political arm of an organization headed by political 
extremist lyndon larouche 
they were convicted of violating a federal regulation banning 
soliciting electioneering collecting debts vending and 
advertising on postal property 
although there was no evidence the two had blocked or interfered 
with people entering or leaving the post office postal officials 
had received about 40 complaints before asking ms kokinda and 
pearl to leave 
the post office in bowie like tens of thousands in suburban and 
rural communities is a freestanding building with its own sidewalk 
and parking lot a municipal sidewalk runs in front of the post 
office property separating the parking lot from the street 
when the case was argued before the high court in february a 
justice department lawyer drew a distinction between municipal 
sidewalks where freespeech rights traditionally have broad 
protections and sidewalks on federal property 
the court today agreed with that distinction 
justice department lawyer john roberts jr last february also 
reported that the regulation is not being enforced against people 
who hand out leaflets or those who picket but only against those 
who solicit immediate contributions 
the case is us vs kokinda 882031 
</TEXT>
