<TEXT>
minority broadcasters said wednesdays supreme 
court decision upholding the federal communications commissions 
affirmative action rules will spur efforts to increase minority 
ownership of radio and tv stations 
james l winston executive director of the national association 
of blackowned broadcasters said the decision means the fccs 
ability to help promote minority ownership can now go forward 
without fear of constitutional challenge 
while this still is not at the level we would like to see 
we are pleased that the ability of the fcc to utilize policies to 
increase ownership will be allowed to continue and expand 
before the fcc established the rules in 1978 blacks owned about 
30 radio stations and one television station according to the 
national association of blackowned broadcasters now blacks own 
182 radio stations and 17 television stations the group said 
wednesday 
that represents an increase from 1 percent to about 35 percent 
of the nations radio and tv stations the fcc said 
those numbers are likely to grow now that the legal 
uncertainties have been lifted from the rules broadcasters said 
eddie fritts president of the national association of 
broadcasters said the decision affirms the fccs ability to 
improve the underrepresentation of minorities in broadcast 
ownership 
lois wright vice president and corporate counsel for one of the 
nations largest blackowned broadcasting companies inner city 
broadcasting corp in new york city said the fcc rules have been 
working effectively and i think theyll work more effectively 
now youre likely to get more deals involving minority 
broadcasters 
the rules upheld wednesday award preference to minorities 
seeking broadcast licenses the fcc comparative licensing 
process also gives preference to competing applicants based on 
other factors such as whether prospective owners plan to operate 
the station female applicants also receive extra points but the 
court said it was not ruling on gender preference 
the court wednesday also upheld separate rules known as the 
distress sale policy that allow a broadcaster faced with the 
loss of his license to sell to a minorityowned business at 75 
percent of a stations market value 
im overjoyed said kernie anderson general manager of 
wdasamfm in philadelphia this reflects a continuation of a 
policy that has benefited not only africanamericans but women and 
the entire nation it has made for greater diversity in our 
industry anderson said 
for the supreme court to uphold the righteousness of what 
indeed was a just action by the commission is appreciated by an 
africanamerican anderson said 
wdas was one of the first stations sold under the distress sale 
policy 
fcc policy also allows anyone who sells a radio or tv station or 
cable system to defer capital gains taxes on the sale if the buyer 
is a member of a minority this socalled tax certificate policy 
was not in question wednesday at the court 
