<TEXT>
czechoslovakias internal security agency tested 
semtex on a passenger aircraft in 1984 and found that just seven 
ounces of the explosive could destroy a plane in flight according 
to a british television documentary 
semtex has been implicated in the destruction of pan am flight 
103 in december 1988 in which 270 people died 
the hourlong this week documentary for thames television 
scheduled for broadcast thursday night shows spectacular 
explosions filmed by the former marketing director at the factory 
that produced semtex 
the tests in october and november of 1984 were an antiterrorist 
exercise said maj zbynek hybl identified as a member of the 
parliamentary special operations group allied with the 
czechoslovak secret police 
hybl said only four other people were involved in the tests 
which were conducted on a sovietbuilt ilyushin 18 he said the 
results were not passed to any terrorist group 
paul wilkinson professor of international relations at st 
andrews university in scotland and an expert on terrorism said in 
a telephone interview that czechoslovakia had no need for an 
antiterrorist program 
there was never a terrorist threat within czechoslovakias 
borders nor had a czech aircraft ever been threatened by attack 
with a sabotage bomb wilkinson said 
czechoslovakias previous communist government had a 
reputation for passing on specialized knowledge not only to their 
own operatives but on a very selective basis to chosen proxies and 
clients which i assume and i think most students of the subject 
assume had to be approved at a very high level with the 
knowledge and consent of the kgb he said 
semtex is made only in czechoslovakia and president vaclav 
havel has confirmed that the previous communist regime sold nearly 
1000 tons of it to the government of libyas col moammar gadhafi 
the documentary says hybls special operations group was 
based in brezany castle near prague where the interior ministry 
also had a training program for third world security agents 
we wanted to find out what strength of charge you would need 
to blow a hole through the fuselage of the plane said hybl 
whose remarks were translated by thames television 
that was the most important piece of information we needed we 
tried every explosive we could get hold of everything from 
military to civilian 
as far as the czechoslovakian explosives we had were 
concerned we discovered that a charge weighing 200 grams seven 
ounces would be more than enough to blow a hole in the fuselage 
which would be large enough to cause the plane to decompress in 
flight 
those tests produced jagged holes about the size of a dinner 
plate in the plane 
scottish police have said pan am flight 103 a boeing 747 was 
