<TEXT>
despite international 
criticism nelson mandela has not renounced violent struggle 
against apartheid because of fears of losing black supporters and a 
major bargaining chip 
mandelas african national congress says it cannot disavow 
violence until apartheid is abolished the anc says it must keep 
its armed wing as long as the government and rightwing white 
groups retain massive military power and unarmed black protesters 
are being killed 
black leaders caution against comparing the antiapartheid 
struggle to the nonviolent civil rights movement in the american 
south in the 1960s nonviolence is not realistic in a country 
where the white government has used force for decades to suppress 
blacks they say 
civil rights movements in the united states were often aimed at 
local governments and laws instead of the federal government 
federal courts and troops often acted to protect civil rights 
activists and restrain local officials and police 
despite controversy in the united states and europe over 
mandelas refusal to renounce violence the anc has all but 
suspended its armed struggle due to several factors 
the legalization of the anc in february a call for negotiations 
by president fw de klerk and reductions in aid from the soviet 
union and eastern europe have led the anc to stop highprofile 
attacks 
even before these developments the ancs armed struggle never 
posed a serious threat to the government 
mandela launched the guerrilla campaign in 1961 a year after 
the anc was outlawed but attempts to build an effective military 
force in south africa failed because of internal problems and the 
superiority of security forces 
the few attacks blamed on the anc in recent months have been 
hitandrun attacks on police stations or government buildings that 
caused minor damage such attacks appear to be the work of small 
groups operating independently and there has been no evidence of 
the anc directing any operations 
but the armed struggle has had a strong psychological impact on 
whites and been a major symbol of resistance to many blacks young 
blacks believe the armed struggle has been the one way they have 
been able to fight apartheid 
mandela risks losing the support of thousands of blacks if he 
renounces the armed struggle before apartheid is abolished such 
young blacks hardened by decades of violence and repression 
glorify strength and believe only violence can end apartheid 
many of the youngsters are not really interested in 
negotiation in fact they have become a little bit angry anc 
leader walter sisulu said 
radical groups that espouse violence such as the pan african 
congress claim they are attracting thousands of former anc members 
disillusioned by mandelas moderate line the anc and allied groups 
are locked in a violent struggle with rival black organizations 
that has cost thousands of lives 
antiapartheid leader archbishop desmond tutu and other 
religious leaders have urged the anc to at least suspend the armed 
struggle to help build peace 
but the threat of armed struggle is one of the ancs best 
bargaining chips in pending negotiations with the government on 
ending apartheid the anc says it cannot renounce violence without 
similar government concessions 
mandela and other black leaders say the government retains 
massive military and police power and that blacks are still 
suffering oppression dozens of blacks have been killed by police 
gunfire in recent months including at least 11 in one incident 
mandela also points to extreme rightwing groups with thousands 
of members that are forming paramilitary groups to resist attempts 
to end white rule blacks must be able to defend themselves because 
the white government will not suppress such groups he says 
