genetically altered potatoes that could be 
naturally deadly to beetles are being field tested in the pacific 
northwest the agriculture department said wednesday 
the outdoor tests were scheduled to begin this week in prosser 
wash said geneticist charles r brown of the departments 
agricultural research service 
ultimately we want to know whether potato plants could use 
this genetic weapon to combat colorado potato beetles with little 
or no chemical insecticide he said 
brown is based at the agencys vegetable and crop research unit 
in prosser and is collaborating with other scientists from the 
university of washington seattle and another usda researcher in 
yakima wash 
the quarteracre potato plots are at washington state 
universitys research and extension center in prosser 
brown said the added gene is from a strain of bacterium 
bacillus thuringiensis or bt that lives in soil naturally and 
makes a beetlekilling protein 
the prosser tests were said to be the first in the united states 
involving bt genes placed in potatoes other researchers at private 
companies and universities however have raised tomato cotton and 
tobacco plants that use a bt gene and show pest resistance 
brown said the colorado potato beetle is probably the worst 
potato insect pest worldwide and that it has become resistant to 
many pesticides 
