<TEXT>
environmental officials proposed a 160 million 
global fund wednesday to help developing nations build industries 
that do not rely on chemicals that damage the earths protective 
ozone layer 
they also offered to increase the fund by 80 million if china 
and india sign a treaty on saving the ozone layer the two 
countries have refused to sign the treaty because they fear the 
high cost of converting to ozonefriendly technology 
the unprecedented idea was announced at the start of a 
conference of environmental ministers and officials from about 100 
countries the fund would be voluntary but it could become a 
future model for how to pay for resolving environmental problems 
the united states which until two weeks ago opposed creating 
such a fund was posing one of the few obstacles to final 
agreement it demanded a permanent seat on the proposed 15member 
executive committee that would decide how to use the money most 
delegates favor rotating membership 
richard smith who led the us delegation in talks this week 
that led to the proposal noted that the united states would 
contribute about 25 percent of the fund our position is that any 
country contributing this much should be permanently on the 
committee he said 
some delegates speaking privately said the united states was 
prepared to compromise and final agreement would be reached by the 
time the meeting ends friday 
delegates are representing the 56 countries that signed the 
montreal protocol of 1987 that treaty called for a 50 percent 
reduction in the manufacture of chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs by 
1996 
the plan for the 160 million global fund was worked out in 
talks that preceded the formal conference 
dr mostafa tolba an egyptian scientist and executive director 
of the un environment program said delegates proposed increasing 
the fund by 80 million if china and india signed the montreal 
protocol 
far too much is at stake to contemplate failure we have no 
option but to succeed and inshallah god willing we will 
succeed he said 
british prime minister margaret thatcher said her government 
would make an initial contribution of 9 million 
we need to speed up action and set ourselves higher targets 
and shorter deadlines for reducing and eventually eliminating cfcs 
and halons she told delegates 
cfcs used in refrigeration insulation cleaning solvents and 
as aerosol propellents rise into the stratosphere where they break 
down in constituent chemical parts one of these chlorine 
destroys the thin shield of ozone that filters out harmful 
ultraviolet rays 
scientists say that without the shield life on earth would 
perish 
