<TEXT>
boris yeltsin on wednesday ordered a freeze on new 
atomic energy projects beginning next year in the russian republic 
that comprises threequarters of the soviet unions territory 
a directive from the republics parliament signed by yeltsin as 
russian president and distributed by the official news agency tass 
charged that national government ministries are illequipped to 
process and store radioactive wastes 
the move highlighted concern about nuclear power in the wake of 
the 1986 chernobyl accident and was the reformminded russian 
presidents first direct challenge to the kremlin since he was 
elected last month 
the directive also called on the russian republics government 
to develop a proposal for banning the burial on russian territory 
of radioactive waste from other nations or in the other 14 soviet 
republics also beginning next year 
it was not immediately clear whether the order would cause a 
direct confrontation between yeltsins government and national 
officials over any specific projects 
a rising antinuclear mood across the entire soviet union has 
forced soviet officials to delay or cancel several nuclear power 
plants the last four years 
yeltsins directive also said the ministry of the sea fleet and 
the defense ministry added to the problem of nuclear waste the 
order did not directly say military nuclear projects must be frozen 
as well but appeared to include them 
the sevenpoint directive cited increasing stockpiles of 
radioactive wastes and the low technological level of the 
management approach to solving the problem of gathering processing 
and eliminating radioactive wastes 
it said that combination created an unhealthy ecological and 
socialpsychological situation in a series of regions of the 
russian republic 
the directive said the russian republic would ask that the 
kremlin write a program for dealing with radioactive waste that 
includes a time period for implementation and delineates 
responsiblity it called for the program to be worked out before 
june 1991 
the russian government was instructed to review all existing 
radioactive waste sites in its jurisdiction and make 
recommendations about how and whether they should be used 
until a national program is enacted the directive said it would 
be considered unacceptable to start construction of new atomic 
energy sites on the territory of the russian republic from jan 1 
1991 
the russian council of ministers was instructed to prepare a 
proposal to prohibit burial on the territory of the russian 
republic the final products of the activity of atomic sites from 
other republics and countries beginning jan 1 1991 
official reports say 31 people were killed when one of four 
reactors at the chernobyl plant in the ukraine caught fire and 
exploded april 26 1986 unofficial reports say 250 died 
the blast spewed cesium strontium and plutonium over a wide 
area of the ukraine byelorussia and russia and also sent a cloud 
of radioactive gas around the world 
this april on the eve of the fourth anniversary of the 
accident the soviet government decided to resettle 200000 more 
people living in the area of the chernobyl plant at a cost of about 
26 billion 
but soviets increasingly concerned about contamination of their 
environment also are worried about the safety of nuclear energy 
used in industry and to power ships such as ice breakers and 
submarines 
the soviet government has only recently acknowledged other major 
nuclear accidents last june officials said that in 1957 a tank of 
radioactive waste exploded at a weapons site in the southern ural 
mountains showering almost 400 square miles with radioactive waste 
and forcing evacuation of 10000 people 
