the supreme court upheld arizonas death 
penalty law wednesday in a decision that also removed a 
constitutional shadow from similar laws in idaho and montana 
by a 54 vote the court said the arizona law is valid even 
though judges not juries decide whether a murderers sentence 
should be death or life in prison 
had the justices ruled the other way new proceedings could have 
been required for the 88 people on arizonas death row and perhaps 
for all or most of the death row inmates in idaho and montana as 
of last month idaho had 19 inmates on death row montana had six 
no one has been executed in those three states since the supreme 
court allowed states to resume capital punishment in 1976 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals which has jurisdiction 
over nine western states including arizona idaho and montana 
previously issued a decision in conflict with the arizona supreme 
courts ruling in waltons case 
the federal appeals court threw out the death sentence of john 
harvey adamson convicted of murdering phoenix newspaper reporter 
