<TEXT>
the chairman of the house foreign aid 
subcommittee said wednesday he will support cuts in aid to israel 
next year if its government persists in expanding settlements in 
the occupied west bank and gaza strip 
the blunt warning came as the house approving a 157 billion 
foreign aid bill narrowly voted to preserve president bushs 
policy of not sending us aid to international family planning 
groups linked to abortion and agreed to keep money flowing to 
cambodias noncommunist resistance the vote on final passage was 
308 to 117 
rep david obey treading on a subject seldom mentioned openly 
in washington said he meant the comments as a very friendly 
warning intended to avoid longterm tragedy and a mountain of 
death in the increasingly unstable region 
if israel expands their settlements in any way or if they add 
a single new settlement i will make a flat commitment to support 
any request made by the administration to reduce aid to israel in 
next years bill the wisconsin democrat said he was opening 
debate on a 158 billion foreign aid bill for the fiscal year 
beginning oct 1 
obeys statement set him on a collision course with the newly 
installed rightwing israeli government which has promised to 
expand settlements in the territories seized in the 1967 sixday 
war 
obey said the amount of any aid cuts would be based on how much 
is spent on creating new settlements or expanding present ones 
israel is a sovereign nation and has the right to do anything 
they want but the us government has no obligation to fund 
either directly or indirectly settlements which we believe to be 
an impediment to the peace process he said 
the bill before the house included 3 billion in military and 
economic aid to israel which traditionally has been the largest 
single foreign recipient of us largesse a separate measure 
passed earlier this year included an additional 400 million in 
loan guarantees to build housing in israel for soviet jewish 
emigres 
ariel sharon the housing minister of the new israeli 
government has said israel will not settle any of the soviet 
emigres in the west bank or gaza and obey welcomed that promise as 
a positive step but his threat to cut aid applied to any 
settlement whether by emigres or others 
on the population issue the house voted 224 to 198 to send 3 
million through private groups for family planning and other health 
projects in romania whose people have for decades been subject to 
a government policy against contraception 
but the amendment offered by rep christopher smith rnj 
specifically excluded from participation two groups the united 
nations population fund and the international planned parenthood 
federation which participate in abortion counseling referral or 
services 
smiths opponents argued that those two groups are the only ones 
which now operate in romania so barring them would make any aid 
program for that country ineffective but smith and allies 
countered that bush would veto any bill that included funding for 
the two abortionlinked agencies 
