abortion services are getting harder to find 
in rural parts of the country and in some areas women have to 
travel hundreds of miles to a provider a report by the alan 
guttmacher institute said wednesday 
nearly all of the nearly 16 million abortions performed in 1988 
were performed in metropolitan areas about 17 percent a total 
of 27000 took place in rural areas according to the survey by 
the independent nonprofit research group 
in 1979 when 15 million abortions were performed in this 
country about 45 percent of them around 67000 were in rural 
facilities 
as the concentration of abortion services has continued to shift 
from hospitals to specialized clinics women in rural areas have 
been hit hardest those women usually have had to rely on hospitals 
for abortion services since small clinics often are not economical 
in rural areas the report said 
our findings clearly show that access to abortion which was 
already a tremendous problem for women living outside of the 
metropolitan areas of our country is getting worse even without 
additional state restrictions that may result from any new 
legislative activity stanley henshaw author of the report said 
in a statement released with it 
in south dakota for example women living in the western and 
central parts of the state have to travel as far as 200 miles to 
the nearest abortion provider the report said 
it said that because of the long distances rural women are more 
likely to have their abortion later in pregnancy when the health 
risks are greater 
