<TEXT>
a judge wednesday issued an 
arrest warrant for an army officer accused of destroying evidence 
in the november massacre of six jesuit priests their cook and her 
teenage daughter 
the warrant comes after widespread criticism of the 
investigation by a us congressional committee and leaders of el 
salvadors roman catholic church 
the charges accuse lt col carlos camilo hernandez of 
destroying the mission logs of troops accused in the shootings at 
central american university 
hernandez an executive officer of the elite belloso battalion 
in san salvador is the former assistant director of the military 
college where the troops were stationed 
the warrant was issued by judge ricardo zamora who is handling 
the politically charged investigation it asks military officials 
to arrest hernandez and hand him over to the civilian court for 
prosecution 
neither the armed forces press office nor the us embassy would 
comment on the latest development in the jesuit case 
defense attorney joaquin barahona said the judge based his 
warrant on the testimony of several witnesses as well as statements 
by hernandez himself 
hernandez is the tenth person charged in the case 
the director of the military college col guillermo benavides 
three lieutenants and five enlisted men have been charged with the 
slayings 
no salvadoran officer has ever been prosecuted for a human 
rights crime despite the deaths of tens of thousands of people at 
the hands of death squads linked to the armed forcesor president 
alfredo cristianis rightist republican nationalist alliance 
to date the only evidence presented against benavides has been 
that of other defendants which is not admissible in salvadoran 
courts 
however a key military witness appeared before the judge 
wednesday in a closed hearing 
col carlos armando aviles who reportedly blew the case open by 
telling a us military adviser who was responsible for the 
slayings arrived wednesday in el salvador from taiwan where he 
had been sent for military training after the jesuit massacre 
aviles is a key witness a defense lawyer requesting 
anonymity told the associated press if he testifies to what he 
has said unofficially it will be overwhelming evidence against the 
defendants 
asked about the latest developments in the jesuit case at a news 
conference wednesday cristiani would only comment if the judge 
thinks he has proof he should proceed according to the law 
the massacre took place amid a huge offensive by leftist rebels 
of the farabundo marti national liberation front who have waged a 
