<DOCNO> AP900627-0178 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a focusing flaw that cannot be repaired from 
the ground has been found in the hubble space telescope leaving 
some instruments unworkable until a repair shuttle mission can be 
flown nasa announced wednesday 
many of the spectacular views of the universe that scientists 
hoped to get with the 15 billion hubble instrument will not be 
possible now until a maintenance mission scheduled for 1993 is 
completed officials said 
nasa said it would try to fly the repair mission earlier 
engineers discovered the flaw when they attempted to finetune 
the focus between the primary and the secondary mirrors aboard the 
orbiting telescope 
hubble deputy project manager jean olivier said there was no 
single one pointwith a crisp clean image 
further study determined that there was a fundamental flaw that 
may have been built in when the mirrors were manufactured olivier 
said during a news conference 
jack rehnberg the chief of the space science program at hughes 
danbury optical of danbury conn manufacturer of the flawed 
mirrors said the cause may have been human error during an 
extensive testing program while the mirrors were being made 
we dont know the cause but its probably something 
inherently fundamentally not done right he said it could 
have been a human error 
the mistake he said could have come with equipment that 
checked the polished mirror surface nasa has said that tests 
showed that hubbles 94inch primary mirror is the smoothest large 
mirror ever made 
we could have erred in the assembly of some of the test 
equipment and it didnt get picked up even though weve had lots of 
reviews and checks and rechecks said rehnberg 
the space agency has named lew allen director of the jet 
propulsion laboratory to head a team investigating the hubble 
problem rehnberg said he has selected a team of engineers from his 
company to help 
nasa scientist ed weiler said the problem degrades the focus 
possible with several instruments aboard the orbiting telescope 
particularly two cameras designed to take pictures in visible light 
of very faint and distant stars 
he said a faint object camera provided to the hubble project by 
the european space agency will not be able to take pictures of a 
quality any better than a groundbased telescope 
a wide field camera which was used to take the first photos 
from the hubble released to the public will be virtually useless 
until the telescope can be repaired 
there is no real science we can do with it at this time he 
said 
three instruments that can study stars by gathering ultraviolet 
and infrared radiation will not be as seriously affected weiler 
said but he noted that one of these instruments the high speed 
photometer will be about to collect about half of the science 
that had been planned 
the hubble was placed in a 281mile high orbit by space shuttle 
discovery on april 25 engineers have spent the time since trying 
to finetune the telescope and test its instruments and have 
repeatedly reported problems 
engineers first discovered that a cable not installed properly 
was blocking the rotation of an antenna this was corrected by 
limiting the antenna movement 
later they found that incorrect computer software was causing 
the telescope to point at the wrong places in the sky the software 
was changed 
the experts also discovered that the 25500pound satellite 
developed a vibration that lasted for some minutes each time it 
went from sunrise to sunset and back again in its orbit engineers 
planned to compensate for the vibration with another computer 
program 
but there is no way to fix the focusing flaw from the ground 
said weiler instead he said nasa plans to try to move up a 
scheduled space shuttle maintenance flight to the telescope 
weiler said a replacement widefield camera that had already 
been scheduled for the hubble may be built with special optics that 
would correct the focusing distortion caused by the telescope 
mirrors 
we are pretty optimistic that we can take out all of the 
aberration said weiler 
hubble maintenance flights by the space shuttle were originally 
planned for 1993 1996 and 1997 and weiler said those may be flown 
earlier if replacement instruments that correct the focusing flaw 
can be prepared 
we are not losing science he said we are deferring 
science 
olivier who has been a leader in checking out the telescope 
said that engineers saw a pattern in their tests that had the 
classical characteristic you would expect for a spherical 
aberration where light does not focus at a point as intended 
but over a small volume 
the two mirrors were tested individually on the ground said 
olivier and passed all tests he said they were not tested in 
combination on the ground because this would have required a test 
arrangement that would have cost hundreds of millions of 
dollars 
before launch the agency said the five instruments aboard would 
detect objects 25 times fainter than the dimmest seen from earth 
and would expand the size of the observable universe by 250 times 
objects in the farthest reaches of the universe some 14 billion 
light years or 82 billion trillion miles away were expected to be 
visible since the universe is thought to be 15 to 20 billion years 
old the telescope would be seeing objects only a short time after 
the socalled big bang that astronomers believe is the origin of 
the universe 
</TEXT>
