<TEXT>
leaders of the unions striking eastern 
airlines and greyhound lines on tuesday urged organized labor to 
push congress to ban hiring of permanent replacement workers 
workers in the usa have in theory the right to strike but 
they dont have the right to win a strike george kourpias 
international president of the machinists union told the american 
federation of state county and municipal employees convention 
both eastern struck by the machinists on march 4 1989 and 
greyhound struck by its drivers march 2 have continued to operate 
with replacement workers 
companion bills by us rep william clay dmo and sen 
howard metzenbaum dohio would prevent companies from giving 
permanent status to workers hired during a strike the bills are 
pending in committees 
easterns pledge to protect its replacement workers has become a 
major sticking issue between its unions and trustee martin shugrue 
appointed in april to run the airline after creditors lost faith in 
the management led by chairman frank lorenzo 
what im really afraid of is that the trustee appointed is 
talking out of both sides of his mouth kourpias said 
kourpias said that while shugrue made obtaining labor peace a 
priority he protects scabs who have taken our jobs the 
airline needs the experience and dedication of the strikers for 
longterm survival kourpias said 
kourpias said more negotiations are expected this week between 
eastern and its machinists led by district president charles e 
bryan 
were ready to go back to work with a new labor agreement 
kourpias said 
a planned meeting between shugrue and eastern creditors was 
postponed tuesday 
the eastern pilots and flight attendants unions ended sympathy 
walkouts last november but they have expressed frustration that 
eastern has hired back only handfuls of union workers while keeping 
replacement workers 
james lasala president of the amalgamated transit union 
representing greyhound drivers said his union like easterns 
machinists felt they were forced to strike because of 
unionbusting tactics 
no matter what happens in this strike our union will still be 
here lasala said 
but hiring replacement workers who can keep their jobs after 
strikes gives companies an unfair boost in overcoming strikes he 
said 
organized labor should hold accountable politicians who allow 
management to have such unfair advantages lasala said now its 
time for them to show us their support 
richard l trumka president of the united mine workers of 
america gave a stirring call for solidarity and political pressure 
in the 1990s following his unions strike at west virginia last 
year which he said was successful because of the belief that 
working people in this country had finally had enough 
the labor meeting will host south african antiapartheid leader 
nelson mandela on thursday 
