<TEXT>
scientists were dismayed wednesday after 
learning that a problem with the hubble space telescopes mirrors 
will render its cameras almost useless until a space shuttle can be 
sent on a repair mission 
its a major blow to our hopes said kim leschly of the 
national aeronautics and space administrations jet propulsion 
laboratory in pasadena it is very disappointing extremely 
disappointing 
david koo an astronomer at the university of california santa 
cruz learned of the telescopes woes when a reporter called 
seeking his reaction 
gee your mom died how do you feel he replied 
koo had planned to analyze the hubbles photographs of random 
patches of the universe to look for unexpected discoveries 
many people were hoping to see new views of the universe now 
well have to wait he said thats very very disappointing 
nasa had planned to make repairs in june 1993 and said it may 
move up that mission 
people arent crying said john holtzman an astronomer at 
lowell observatory in flagstaff ariz its just that there have 
been so many delays in this project that when you say wait another 
three years its slightly depressing 
holtzman was interviewed by phone from a telescope science team 
office near goddard space flight center in maryland 
nasa officials announced wednesday that a manufacturing error 
prevents proper focusing of the 15 billion telescopes mirrors 
they said that until space shuttle astronauts can make repairs 
the problem will make the telescopes most important instrument 
the widefield and planetary camera virtually useless 
the flaw also will make the telescopes second camera which is 
designed to detect faint distant objects unable to take pictures 
any better than those taken by a groundbased telescope three 
other instruments which detect various types of light but arent 
cameras will be less seriously impaired 
the reaction at jet propulsion laboratory which built the 
widefield camera was how come people making the mirror didnt 
do their job right said leschly the cameras systems engineer 
as part of the hubble team you feel disappointed somebody didnt 
do it right and that hurts 
the mirrors and their supports were manufactured by perkinelmer 
corp now hughes danbury optical corp of danbury conn 
company official jack rehnberg said human error may have been to 
blame 
nasa officials in washington said they may correct the problem 
by modifying a secondgeneration widefield camera now under 
construction at the pasadena laboratory the new camera could be 
equipped with special optics to compensate for the focusing flaw 
caused by the faulty mirrors leschly said 
astronauts had been scheduled to replace the existing widefield 
camera with the new camera in june 1993 but nasa indicated it 
would try to fly the repair mission earlier 
there is a path out of this and there still will be images 
from the current camera that will be reasonably exciting but they 
wont push the frontier leschly said adding that the camera 
works flawlessly but is crippled by the mirror problem 
were down for a while but on our way up he said you 
can still see hope at the end of the tunnel 
</TEXT>
