<TEXT>
an anonymous caller saying he spoke on 
behalf of colombian guerrillas who allegedly kidnapped scott 
heimdal told a television station wednesday that the american would 
be killed if ransom demands werent met 
the caller a male who spoke with a colombian accent said the 
group holding heimdal a gold miner was the same one that 
kidnapped spanish businessman pablo martin berrocal last august 
the station said 
berrocal was freed in april after his family paid a 1 million 
ransom 
heimdals kidnappers earlier identified themselves as members of 
the peoples liberation army but the anonymous caller said the 
national liberation army was holding heimdal 
diplomatic sources said it was doubtful the national liberation 
army kidnapped heimdal because it operates in northern colombia 
far from the ecuadoran border region where heimdal was captured 
the caller also said iminco the small mining company for which 
heimdal worked received 1 million to be used as ransom but the 
company denied it the caller did not say where the company 
received the money from 
meanwhile the government has ordered iminco to suspend its 
operations the mines owner jeffrey fino said wednesday fino 
said however the company had already suspended its operations 
fino also an american said he did not know the reasons behind 
the suspension which he learned of in a letter received tuesday 
from the ecuadoran institute of mines he said work had stopped at 
the mine when the 27yearold heimdal was kidnapped april 28 
fino said he has not been involved in the negotiations since 
heimdals parents arrived june 18 in quito from peoria ill to 
take charge of efforts to win his release 
a us embassy spokesman refused to comment on either the 
anonymous call or the suspension of finos mining operation 
heimdal was kidnapped as he traveled by boat near the gold 
mining camp where he was in charge of starting river dredging 
operations 
he is reportedly being held in a jungle camp on the colombian 
side of the border 
fino said he suspended mining operations after heimdals 
kidnapping and was selling off his equipment he said the mine 
never reached the production stage 
heimdals kidnappers have asked a ransom of 612000 paid in 
colombian pesos heimdals parents raised about 60000 mostly in 
community donations and that money has been given to the 
guerrillas to assure heimdals safety while negotiations continue 
in washington a government source said on condition of 
anonymity that a meeting is scheduled friday between the kidnappers 
and officials working for heimdals release 
