<TEXT>
lithuanias leaders rushed to moscow on 
wednesday for their second meeting with soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev in two days as they tried to come up with a compromise on 
the republics drive for independence 
lithuanian president vytautas landsbergis and prime minister 
kazimiera prunskiene called gorbachev on wednesday afternoon to 
arrange the meeting it took place a few hours later at gorbachevs 
dacha in the forest outside moscow lithuanian parliament 
spokeswoman rita dapkus said 
lithuanias supreme council or parliament was scheduled to 
begin debating the proposed compromise thursday morning it calls 
for a threemonth moratorium on the republics march 11 declaration 
of independence that would take effect when the soviet union opened 
negotiations said lithuanian government spokesman ceslovas 
jursenas 
the proposal also says the moratorium would cease if the 
lithuanian government becomes unable to perform its duties 
jursenas said 
at the meeting gorbachev reiterated that lithuania must freeze 
its declaration of independence before he would end crippling 
economic sanctions and begin negotiations ms dapkus said 
oil supplies most natural gas and many raw materials and 
manufactured goods have been cut off since midapril when the 
kremlin imposed the embargo to pressure lithuania to rescind its 
independence declaration the blockade has put nearly 50000 people 
out of work among the republics 11 million workers 
gorbachev did not mention his earlier insistence that lithuania 
abide by the law on secession passed by the soviet parliament 
earlier this year said ms dapkus 
lithuanians say the secession law imposes conditions that make 
it impossible for a republic to leave the soviet union the law 
makes secession illegal without a republicwide referendum 
approval by the soviet parliament and a transition period of up to 
five years 
ms dapkus said gorbachev urged the lithuanian parliament to 
take action quickly on the proposed compromise 
gorbachev gave no reason for the urgency she said 
but a critical soviet communist party congress is set to open 
monday and the expected showdown between reformers and hardliners 
could affect gorbachevs political situation 
lithuanian officials also are facing a critical point due to the 
increasingly severe effects of the kremlins economic blockade 
lithuanian government officials said wednesday that they do not 
have enough fuel to begin the grain harvest which should start 
next week they said they soon would have to restrict fuel 
elsewhere and begin cutting back on hot water supplies to homes 
the official soviet news agency tass quoted a lithuanian 
spokesman in moscow virgilius savitskas as saying that during the 
90minute meeting with gorbachev the lithuanian officials were 
searching for a reasonable compromise with gorbachev over the 
republics independence declaration 
tass in its report wednesday night said negotiations could be 
held only if lithuania declares a moratorium and suspends the act 
of march 11 for a period of talks 
it was the second meeting in as many days between lithuanian 
leaders and gorbachev as a divided lithuanian parliament and 
society prepared for the parliamentary debate 
the lithuanian delegation left moscow immediately after the 
talks ended and headed back to vilnius the lithuanian capital on 
a special flight said officials of the republics mission in 
moscow 
accompanying landsbergis and mrs prunskiene were deputy prime 
minister romualdas ozolas legislative leader egidius bickauskas 
and two other lawmakers 
gorbachev met with landsbergis on tuesday morning and spoke with 
mrs prunskiene by telephone two hours later 
ms dapkus said wednesdays meeting carried more weight because 
it also involved soviet prime minister nikolai ryzhkov soviet 
parliamentary chairman anatoly lukyanov and gorbachevs close 
adviser politburo member alexander yakovlev 
at the meeting gorbachev that if lithuania freezes its 
independence declaration the republic could either negotiate 
directly with the soviet government or participate in planned 
negotiations on a new union treaty that would link the 15 soviet 
republics in a looser structure ms dapkus said 
gorbachev urged lithuania to take part in the intersoviet 
treaty ms dapkus said 
gorbachev aides have described this newlook union as anything 
from a federation like the united states to a confederation like 
the european community which allies independent countries 
lithuanian officials said privately a sharp debate was going on 
in the republic on how their drive for independence would be 
affected by the upcoming communist party congress and its effect on 
gorbachevs power 
the lithuanians indicated they do not know if they should accept 
the compromise while gorbachev is strong enough to offer it or 
hold out for possible victory by reformers who support the 
republics right to independence 
lithuania was forcibly annexed by the soviet union in 1940 
along with the baltic republics of latvia and estonia those 
republics have also declared they want to regain their 
independence but have taken a slower approach than lithuania 
</TEXT>
