<TEXT>
as hundreds of companies prepare for shareholder 
meetings thursday japans sokaiya racketeers are gearing up 
for action again seeking hush money to leave the sessions 
undisturbed 
and this year may bring a new group of racketeers backed by 
japans largest underworld syndicate as it seeks to establish a 
foothold in the nations capital police say 
several sokaiya groups that are apparently backed by the 
yamaguchigumi have been increasingly active in western japan and 
some of these are also believed to be opening new operations in the 
tokyo area said a national police agency report 
the 20000plusmember yamaguchigumi syndicate has kept away 
from tokyo in the past but recently has been extending its forces 
nationwide 
sokaiya racketeers often pose as analysts or consultants and 
extort money from companies by threatening to make embarrassing 
comments or otherwise disrupt their annual shareholders meetings 
the national police agency report said there are 1307 sokaiya 
in japan another 123 gangsters are involved in sokaiya activities 
but are not considered fulltime racketeers it said 
tokyo as japans financial center is home to about 900 such 
racketeers said yoshihiro kondo head of the metropolitan police 
departments organized crime division 
kondo said 2600 officers will be called out thursday to 
discourage disturbances at the 780 general shareholders meetings 
scheduled in tokyo a special sokaiya task force is set up in the 
organized crime division each summer 
in the early 1980s police estimated there were 6000 sokaiya 
nationwide who hauled in about 390 million a year through 
blackmail schemes in one year alone 243 sokaiya were arrested 
some for extortion and others for income tax evasion 
sokaiya activity appeared to taper off after a 1982 law made it 
illegal to pay off sokaiya and increased the number of shares 
required to attend shareholders meetings 
but the sokaiya managed to bounce back kondo said 
the decreased numbers of sokaiya in the police agency report 
which was released monday may reflect merely a greater difficulty 
in identifying sokaiya he said 
sokaiya groups recently have been moving away from general 
meetings to concentrate on backstage activities which include 
coercing companies into subscribing to their publications as a form 
of hush money he said 
such publications generally contain material often gleaned from 
company employees that could create a scandal for the company if 
released widely kondo said 
businesses have banded together to fight the sokaiya by holding 
their meetings on the same day on thursday 1666 companies 
nationwide will hold shareholders meetings 
among them is koito manufacturing co which is waging a highly 
publicized battle with american investor t boone pickens pickens 
owns a 26 percent share in the auto parts maker and has demanded a 
seat on its board of directors 
last year pickens calls for increased shareholders rights 
were echoed by a number of questioners from the floor 
toughlooking men in flashy suits who badgered koito management for 
about 90 minutes 
afterward pickens said they had asked some good questions but 
he said of the tactic thats an interesting way to ask for an 
income statement 
this years koito meeting with its second round in the 
highprofile pickens conflict will be a likely target for sokaiya 
kondo said 
