<TEXT>
president bushs decision to postpone oil 
drilling off southern florida leaves in limbo 73 oil leases already 
bought from the government and is likely to prompt a court battle 
over how much the leases are worth 
bush on tuesday imposed a 10year moratorium on oil development 
in environmentally sensitive areas off southern florida as well as 
off the coasts of california washington and new england 
unlike in california where the leases under consideration have 
yet to be put up for sale a group of oil companies already own 73 
leases off florida within the 13 million acres under presidential 
review the leases were purchased in 1983 and 1984 for 108 million 
exploratory drilling would have begun immediately in two of the 
sites if bush had given the goahead 
what happens to the leases now that bush put a hold on further 
oil activity there 
on tuesday bush announced his administration would begin 
negotiations with the state of florida to work out a joint effort 
to purchase the leases from the oil companies that bought them for 
108 million federal officials have said they want florida to bear 
a substantial portion of the cost but the state has indicated 
buying the leases should be left to washington since the federal 
government sold the leases 
the people of florida should not be asked to bear what is 
rightly a federal responsibility gov bob martinez said tuesday 
the oil companies could hold onto them but most industry 
experts doubt they will choose to do so they cite the opposition 
of environmentalists that they say is all but certain to intensify 
the longer drilling is delayed 
were kind of in unchartered territory here says mike 
kimmit a spokesman for mobil oil co which owns 22 of the leases 
he said the leases were acquired with the expectation that drilling 
could be pursued oil would be discovered and a profit could be 
made 
