identically 
in a case from florida the court allowed the commission to give 
special favorable consideration to minorities in awarding a 
television station license 
in a case from connecticut the court upheld the commissions 
socalled distresssale policy which allows a broadcaster faced 
with the loss of its license to sell to a minorityowned business 
at 75 percent of market value 
todays ruling which came in a consolidation of the two cases 
is a surprising victory for affirmative action from a conservative 
supreme court 
throughout the history of the case the fcc has argued womens 
rights were at issue the associated press initially reported that 
the ruling affected both women and minorities but in a footnote in 
his 50page majority opinion justice william j brennan said the 
court did not address gender preferences 
the footnote referring to a broad fcc policy statement says 
the fcc also announced in its 1978 statement a tax certificate 
policy and other minority preferences which are not at issue 
today similarly the commissions gender preference policy is 
not before us today 
legal experts said they are confident the ruling also will 
permit the fcc to continue its policy of giving prefential 
treatment as well to women seeking broadcast licenses although the 
court did not specifically address that issue 
andrew jay schwartzman a communications lawyer said he was 
delighted with the ruling and said preferential treatment for women 
applicants appears to be on safe ground 
a similar policy for women i believe would also be upheld 
he said 
in its most important previous ruling on preferential minority 
treatment by the federal government a more liberal high court in 
1980 upheld a public works program that set aside a percentage of 
federal funds for minority contracts 
more recently however the court has trimmed affirmative action 
programs last year the justices struck down a richmond va 
program that set aside a percentage of local public works contracts 
for minorityowned businesses that ruling cast doubt on the 
validity of numerous similar plans of states and cities but had no 
bearing on federal programs 
todays ruling came as congress and the bush administration 
continue negotiations to settle differences on the proposed civil 
rights act of 1990 a bill aimed at erasing the effects of the 
earlier supreme court decisions weakening affirmative action 
programs 
administration officials say theyre concerned that provisions 
of the bill permitting suits by individuals alleging hiring 
discrimination are so strong in terms of potential damages that 
they would if enacted lead businesses to reinstitute hiring 
quotas 
the bill as now written goes beyond the traditional 
discrimination remedies of restoration of job and back pay 
today the justices said they owe special deference to federal 
programs that give preferential treatment to minorities 
brennan writing for the court said 
it is of overriding significance in these cases that the fccs 
minority ownership programs have been specifically approved 
indeed mandated by congress 
we hold that benign raceconscious measures mandated by 
congress even if those measures are not remedial in the sense of 
being designed to compensate victims of past governmental or 
societal discrimination are constitutionally permissible to the 
extent that they serve important governmental objectives within the 
power of congress and are substantially related to achievement of 
those objectives 
brennan was joined by justices byron r white thurgood 
marshall harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
the dissenters were chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices sandra day oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
oconnor in an opinion joined by the other dissenters said the 
ruling violates fundamental principles requiring the government 
to treat all americans equally 
the court departs from these fundamental principles and from 
our traditional requirement that racial classifications are 
permissible only if necessary and narrowly tailored to achieve a 
compelling interest she said 
the fcc said its policies adopted in 1978 are intended to 
promote diversity over the nations airwaves by letting missing 
voices be heard on radio and television 
but the commission has not always supported affirmative action 
wholeheartedly when ronald reagan was president the fcc 
considered scrapping the policies 
the current commission has called for broadening minority 
representation in the broadcast industry but the bush 
administrations justice department has disagreed with the fccs 
policies 
justice department lawyers told the court that the affirmative 
action policies are invalid because congress did not initiate them 
and design them narrowly to correct past bias 
but congress expressed itself on the issue in 1987 by passing an 
appropriations bill that barred the fcc from spending any money to 
review or scrap its affirmative action policies 
the fccs support for affirmative action has had limited 
success the commission said minorities control 35 percent of the 
nations radio and tv stations compared to less than 1 percent in 
1978 
other federal affirmative action programs have been adopted by 
the transportation and defense departments and by the small 
business administration 
in the florida case the fcc awarded hispanicowned rainbow 
broadcasting co a new tv license in orlando a threejudge federal 
appeals court panel in the district of columbia upheld by the 
high court ruled that a rival metro broadcasting inc was not 
denied the license unfairly 
in the connecticut case a different panel of the same appeals 
court struck down the fccs distresssale policy and ordered 
hispanicled astroline communications co to surrender its license 
for whcttv in hartford the appeals court reversed by the 
justices ruled for rival broadcaster alan shurberg who is white 
james l winston executive director of the national association 
of blackowned broadcasters said the courts decision means the 
fccs ability to help promote minority ownership can now go forward 
without fear of constitutional challenge 
the polices have been effective over the past 12 years in 
increasing the number of minorityowned stations in general and 
particularly the ownership by africanamericans from 30 radio 
stations and one television station to the point where we now have 
182 radio stations and 17 television stations 
said kernie anderson general manager of blackowned wdasfmam 
in philadelphia one of the first stations sold under the distress 
sale policy 
this reflects a continuation of a policy that has benefited 
not only africanamericans but women and the entire nation it has 
made for greater diversity in our industry for the supreme court 
to uphold the righteousness of what indeed was a just action by the 
commission is appreciated by an africanamerican 
the cases acted upon today are metro broadcasting vs fcc 
89453 and astroline communications vs shurberg broadcasting 
89700 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

