<TEXT>
talks between japan and the united states on 
structural trade reforms progressed late wednesday night with a 
lastminute breakthrough on the issue of increasing japans public 
works spending officials said 
prime minister toshiki kaifu conveyed japans final offer on the 
issue to president george bush in a telephone conversation late 
wednesday night 
bush said he would hear details of the talks from us officials 
and expressed appreciation for kaifus efforts according to a 
highranking foreign ministry official 
this represents a breakthrough said the official who spoke 
on condition of anonymity without an agreement on public works 
spending tonight i doubt we could finish the talks by tomorrow 
foreign ministry officials said they could not confirm reports 
that japanese and us officials had agreed on a final figure of 
277 trillion in public works spending over the next 10 years 
local media citing unidentified government sources said kaifu 
and other top japanese officials meeting in a lastditch move to 
salvage the talks had agreed to increase their original proposal 
of 268 trillion by 9677 billion 
us officials accepted the proposal kyodo news service 
reported 
the united states claims that japan needs to offset its high 
savings rate which gives japanese businesses a relatively cheaper 
source of capital than their us counterparts with more 
government spending which can boost such capital costs as interest 
rates 
washington had requested that tokyo commit itself to spending at 
least 322 trillion over the next decade 
japanese officials expressed concern that such a large increase 
would stimulate inflation 
earlier wednesday night us officials had said the talks were 
at an impasse due to conflicts over public works spending and other 
issues despite a decision by bush to take stronger action to cut 
the us budget deficit 
a senior us official participating in the talks complained 
that japan had failed to show political will to match bushs 
decision on tuesday to accept tax increases to help cut the us 
deficit 
it took more political courage to raise tax revenues than it 
would to increase public spending the official said on condition 
he not be named the president made an important decision we 
hope our japanese friends realize that 
doing more to cut its budget deficit is one of washingtons key 
commitments in the current round of trade talks called the 
structural impediments initiative 
the talks are intended to attack japans 49 billion surplus in 
trade with the united states by taking steps to remedy fundamental 
problems in both countries such as the us budget deficit and 
japans toughtocrack business systems seen as hindering trade 
and competitiveness 
this weeks talks were to prepare a final version of an interim 
report issued in april 
officials said they expected to work through the night in order 
to complete the report by midday thursday prior commitments on 
both sides required that the current talks end then or resume 
sometime next week they said 
the meetings originally were scheduled to end tuesday but have 
dragged on as officials haggled over the many topics under 
discussion 
the us official said progress had been made on opening japans 
products distribution system and improving land use and customs 
facilities and operations there also was progress on measures by 
washington to curb demand for imports improve competitiveness of 
us products and slash the federal budget deficit 
but he said negotiators were still split on issues related to 
exclusionary business practices and the speed of processing patent 
applications and over the private right to take legal action over 
unfair business practices 
japanese officials were dissatisfied with us proposals on 
easing export controls for oil and strategically sensitive 
products he said 
both sides say they are anxious to reach agreement before the 
july 9 summit of the seven major industrialized democracies in 
houston 
