states where population is growing rapidly 
the proposal immediately was challenged by lawmakers who 
brandished the sampl collapse as evidence that the northeast already 
is carrying too much baggage for texas and other southern states 
this amendment has the possibilities of creating enormous 
regional animosities of tearing us apart at a time when we need to 
be coming together said sen john kerry dmass 
the senate voted to kill gramms proposal but not before it 
triggered a strong reaction from northern senators of both parties 
sen alfonse damato rny proposed a counteramendment that 
would ensure recipients of bailout money such as texas would lose a 
proportional amount of block grant funding 
damato said congress approved the bailout of the collapsed 
savings and loan industry last year even though most of the money 
would go to a few southwestern states most prominently texas but 
with gramms housing amendment he said the rules have changed 
the citizens of new york will pay taxes to clean up the 
problems elsewhere and be deprived of the economic use of those 
funds damato said worse still the empty office space and 
cheap homes built with sampl money can be used to lure businesses 
away from new york away from connecticut 
gramm shot back that the sampl bailout money wasnt being poured 
into the coffers of the state of texas or its citizens it was 
paying back insured depositors many of them highroller investors 
from the northeast 
he called the idea of using trumped up amendments based on the 
sampl bailout a cute and clever tactic 
to in any way equate the sampl bailout with a formula for 
allocating community development block grant funds a formula that 
in its current incarnation is absolutely unfair is just 
outrageous gramm said im not trying to beat a regional horse 
here 
damato admitted his amendment was more of a symbolic gesture 
than a serious effort at legislation but damato and others said 
the idea of penalizing the southwest reflected a genuine outrage 
over the sampl burden it was placing on the rest of the country 
sen alan dixon dill cited statistics showing the extent to 
which northeastern and midwestern taxpayers will be funneling money 
to the southwest 
texas texas texas dixon bellowed the big winner 
kerry spoke ominously of a farm bill about to come to the 
senate floor with goodies galore for western and southern farm 
states if gramm and others move to tilt other federal programs in 
favor of the sunbelt kerry said the repercussions are going to 
play out as we debate the farm bill 
sen daniel patrick moynihan dny threatened to block a 
water resources development bill containing a substantial amount of 
money for texas moynihan chairs a senate subcommittee handling the 
bill 
