a new truck drivers group is asking 
other truckers to stay off the roads in the united states and 
canada from july 1 through july 4 to protest poor pay and working 
conditions organizers of the proposed shutdown said wednesday 
if the truckers holiday is successful food products will 
be in short supply at grocery stores by july 5 said herman johns 
president of the united truckers alliance and if their demands for 
better pay and working conditions are ignored the bellevillebased 
group wants truckers to stay out until they are met 
we are losing our professional drivers because they cant 
afford to keep driving they must work 90 to 100 hours a week 
said cecilia cece nebgen vice president of uta which was 
formed in february 
the group which says it represents 3000 truckers said that 1 
million of the estimated 27 million overtheroad truck drivers 
are expected to join the effort 
that figure was scoffed at by don tepper spokesman for the 
national private truck council in alexandria va the council 
represents shippers producers and truck carrier companies 
nationwide 
if they expect 1 million drivers to join them then santa 
claus would be leading the way tepper said noting that similar 
calls by other groups in the early 1980s were unsuccessful 
but he conceded that a successful fourday stoppage could leave 
store shelves understocked or bare 
meanwhile in a separate action canadian truck drivers were 
preparing to park their rigs at border crossings at midnight 
thursday to protest government policies in their country that they 
believe are unfair to canadian truckers 
