washington did not return repeated phone calls for comment 
half the membership of the uta formed in february is comprised 
of independent drivers and the other half work for shipping or 
other companies johns said tepper said about 150000 of the 
nations truck drivers are independent or socalled 
owneroperators 
johns said truckers are being driven out of the industry by 
increases in operation costs and decreasing paychecks 
truckers havent had a pay raise in 10 years since 
deregulation took effect he said referring to congressional 
action that eased restrictions on the trucking industry in 1980 
tepper conceded pay is low for some drivers 
some owneroperators are making a nice living and there are 
other operators who are earning very little but its a measurable 
minority he said 
johns said the alliance wants all truck carriers and companies 
that ship goods by truck to 
pay company drivers 32 cents per mile and 16 per hour for all 
time spent driving fueling loading unloading and working around 
the truck company drivers are now paid about 20 cents per mile and 
no hourly wage johns said tepper said they make between 20 and 25 
cents per mile 
pay independent drivers 1 per mile for the use of their 
tractor an additional 20 cents per mile if the trailer is supplied 
by the owneroperator and 16 per hour labor johns said 
independents currently make about 80 cents per mile 
tepper doubted truckers would win their demands 
with the competition in the marketplace and with the number of 
drivers that there are those wage and compensation levels couldnt 
be justified tepper said there are people willing to work for 
less 
