<TEXT>
the senate on wednesday approved overhauling 
federal housing policies and requiring firsttime home buyers to 
pay more for fhabacked mortgages 
the bill which had languished on the senate floor for nearly 
two weeks was approved on a 961 vote after democrats and 
republicans announced agreement on key provisions with the bush 
administration the only no vote was cast by sen william roth 
rdel 
as passed the legislation would authorize 181 billion in 
federal spending on housing in fiscal 1991 195 billion in 1992 
and 21 billion in 1993 compared with the 145 billion being 
spent this year 
the issue now movesto the house where a competing version would 
cost far more money and take a different approach to restructuring 
often scandalprone federal housing programs that have basically 
gone unchanged since 1968 
many problems still face us dealing with the conference with 
house members over their bill said sen alan cranston dcalif 
but he called the compromise and senate vote an important 
breakthrough that could assure passage of a major housing bill this 
year 
housing and urban development secretary jack kemp joined senate 
sponsors including damato and cranston in announcing agreement 
on key elements of the bill 
the administration agreed to authorize spending some 3 billion 
more on federal housing programs next year than president bush 
sought in his proposed budget for fiscal 1991 
in return the administrations socalled homeownership 
opportunity for people everywhere hope program to encourage 
eventual tenant purchase of public housing units was included with 
19 billion over three years 
senate democrats also agreed to accept kemps proposals to make 
home buyers using fha mortgages ante up more of their own money at 
the point of sale as a measure for shoring up the financially 
imperiled program 
under the changes new home buyers with fhabacked loans would 
have to make at least a 5 percent down payment on the purchase 
price and cover at least twothirds of the closing costs out of 
their own pockets without financing 
loans with low down payments deemed most at risk to default 
would also be subject to an added annual fee 
the administration in turn gave senate democrats the housing 
opportunity program hop which would consolidate 10 existing 
housing programs for sending money to local governments to renovate 
or build new housing for lowincome families 
democrats agreed to accept provisions that would allow a portion 
of the money to be spent on vouchers for the poor to use for rental 
housing despite the senates rejection of a similar proposal last 
week 
the senate passed the bill after spending much of the day using 
it as a vehicle to argue about which regions of the country were 
having to spend the most on the savings and loan bailout 
the final hour was spent on debating an amendment by sen jesse 
helms rnc directing negotiators working on a deficit reduction 
package to cut a wide variety of federal programs and subsidies 
before raising taxes president bush on tuesday said a tax increase 
is needed in addition to spending cuts 
helms amendment was later accepted on a voice vote after it was 
watered down to say that the negotiators should consider the most 
feasible budget reduction proposals from a wide variety of groups 
before considering new or increased taxes 
earlier rancorous debate centered on a proposal by sen phil 
gramm rtexas to shift community development subsidies in the 
housing bill from the northeast to texas and 35 other states many 
in the sun belt his amendment would have changed distribution 
formula for the 3 billion in block grants to one based solely on 
population 
the senate voted to table or kill gramms proposal on a 6335 
vote after it triggered a strong reaction from northern senators 
who charged texas and the southwest have benefited most from the 
massive federal spending on covering sampl losses 
the people of new york are going to pay 17 billion for the 
savings and loan bailout said sen alfonse damato rny 
the state of texas gets 59 percent of that why should 
every man woman and child have to pony up money to pay for that 
damato said 
he retaliated with an amendment that would reduce community 
development grants to states with savings and loans institutions 
that have been taken over by the federal government it died with 
gramms amendment 
gramms proposal would have replaced a complex formula now in 
use that places greater emphasis on the age of existing housing 
population crowding the number of people in poverty and the rate 
of growth 
im trying to right a terrible wrong in the allocation of 
money gramm said i dont think new york has any room to cry 
about the allocation of funds texas gets cheated by the 
current formula he said 
according to gramms figures new york would suffer a 95 percent 
cut in its community development money from 302 million to 207 
million other states that would lose money would be hawaii 
illinois iowa louisiana maine massachusetts michigan 
mississippi missouri new jersey ohio pennsylvania and rhode 
island 
texas florida and california would be among the biggest 
gainers each getting an increase of more than 20 million 
three senators did not vote on final passage of the bill they 
were sens edward kennedy dmass william armstrong rcolo and 
claiborne pell dri 
